{"title_page": "Starship Entertainment", "text_new": "{{Short description|South Korean record label}}\n{{infobox company\n| name             = Starship Entertainment<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/Research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=253118840 Bloomberg Businessweek]</ref>\n| native_name      = \uc2a4\ud0c0\uc27d \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8\n| native_name_lang = ko\n| logo             = Starship Entertainment.png\n| type             = [[Public]] company \n| traded_as        = \n| founder          = Kim Shi-dae\n| key_people       = Kim Shi-dae (CEO)\n| industry         = {{unbulleted list|[[Entertainment]]|}}\n| genre            = {{unbulleted list|[[K-pop]]|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Electronic Music|Electronic]]|[[Contemporary folk music|Contemporary folk]]}}\n| services         = {{unbulleted list|Music production | Publishing| Artists management}}\n| revenue          = \n| parent           = [[Kakao M]]<br />(since 2013)\n| owner            =  [[Kakao M]] (70%)\n| num_employees    = \n| divisions        = [[King Kong Entertainment|King Kong by Starship]] (since 2015)\n| subsid           = Starship X (2013)<br />House of Music (2017)\n| footnotes        = \n| profit           = \n| slogan           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.starship-ent.com/}}\n| caption          = \n| foundation       = {{Start date|2008|01|28}}\n| former_name      = \n| location_city    = [[Myeongdong]],  [[Seoul]]\n| location_country = [[South Korea]]\n| locations        = \u2022 Bongeunsa-ro<br />\u2022  [[Samseong-dong]]<br />\u2022 [[Gangnam District|Gangnam-gu]] \n}}\n\n'''Starship Entertainment''' ({{ko-hhrm|\uc2a4\ud0c0\uc27d \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8}}) is a South Korean entertainment company established in 2008 by founder Kim Shi Dae.\n\nThe label is home to [[K-Pop]] artists such as [[K.Will]], [[Soyou]], OG School Project, [[Jooyoung]], [[Monsta X]], [[Yoo Seung-woo]], [[Brother Su]], [[Cosmic Girls]], [[Gun (rapper)|#Gun]], [[Mind U]], [[Duetto (duo)|Duetto]], [[Jeong Se-woon]],<ref>[http://search.nate.com/search/all.html?q=%BD%BA%C5%B8%BD%B1+%BF%A3%C5%CD%C5%D7%C0%CE%B8%D5%C6%AE&csn=0&asn=001200370&ml=1&tq=&rq=&nq=2&sg=&fss=&tid=&hlid=&clid=&cbid= \"\uc2a4\ud0c0\uc27d \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8\"], ''Naver''. Retrieved 22 October 2011. {{in lang|ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|script-title=ko:\ubcf4\uc774\ud504\ub80c\ub4dc, \uc6d0\uc22d\uc774 \uc721\ud3ec \ub4dc\uc154\ubcf4\uc168\ub098\uc694?|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20111104n19067|publisher=Nate|accessdate=4 November 2011|language=Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\ubcf4\uc774\ud504\ub80c\ub4dc, \uc77c\ubcf8 NHK \ubc29\uc1a1\ucd9c\uc5f0 '\uc2e0\uc778\ubd88\uad6c \uc774\ub840\uc801 \ud3b8\uc131'|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20111018n04927|publisher=Nate|accessdate=4 November 2011|language=Korean}}</ref> and formerly to [[Sistar]], [[Boyfriend (band)|Boyfriend]], [[Junggigo]], and [[Mad Clown]]. It also manages the actors Choi Won-myeong, [[Dasom]] and Kang Eun-ah. It operates in three main locations and is staffed with approximately 200 employees, funded by both commercial investors and its parent company, [[Kakao M]].\n\n== History ==\nThe company's founder, Kim Shi-dae, previously worked as a road manager for a K-pop band named [[cool (South Korean band)|Cool]] and worked for [[Bang Si-hyuk]]'s company [[Big Hit Entertainment]] between 2005 and 2007 before establishing his own company. Starship's first artist was [[K.Will]], followed by [[Sistar]], [[Boyfriend (band)|Boyfriend]], [[Monsta X]], [[Cosmic Girls]], and [[Jeong Se-woon]].\n\nOn 18 December 2013, 70% of the label's shares was acquired by its distributor, [[Kakao M]] (formerly LOEN Entertainment), making it an independent subsidiary of the latter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2013/12/loen-entertainment-takes-over-majority-stake-in-starship-entertainment-for-15-billion-won|title=Loen Entertainment takes over majority stake in Starship Entertainment for 15 billion won|author=alim17|date=December 18, 2013|work=[[allkpop]]|accessdate=December 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Starship Entertainment had acquired 100% of King Kong Entertainment's shares in a strategic partnership alliance. On 2 January 2017, Starship Entertainment and King Kong Entertainment registered their merger. The agencies mutually agreed to use the name Starship Entertainment while the division that manages the actors will be operating under the label \u201cKing Kong by Starship\u201d.\n\n== Partnerships ==\n* {{Flagicon|JPN}} [[Being Inc.|Being Group]]<ref name=\"being\">{{cite web |title=We Are Boyfriend to be Released on June 6, 2012! |url=http://boyfriend-jp.com/news/120417.html |publisher=[[Being Inc.|Being Group]] |date= |access-date=May 3, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507045135/http://boyfriend-jp.com/news/120417.html |archive-date=May 7, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon|JPN}} Kiss Entertainment\n* {{Flagicon|CHN}} [[Yuehua Entertainment]]\n* {{Flagicon|JPN}} [[Universal Music Japan]]\n\n== Artists ==\nAll artists under Starship Entertainment are collectively known as '''Starship Planet'''.\n\n=== Musicians ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n\n====Soloists====\n* [[K.Will]]\n* [[Soyou]]\n* [[Jeong Se-woon|Jeong Sewoon]]\n\n====Groups====\n* [[Monsta X]]\n* [[Cosmic Girls]] (WJSN) (with [[Yuehua Entertainment]])\n* [[Cravity]]\n\n====Duos/project groups====\n* [[Mind U]]\n* [[Duetto (duo)|Duetto]]\n* YTeen (with [[KT Corporation|KT]])\n*OG School Project (with [[Cube Entertainment]])\n*YDPP (with [[Brand New Music]])\n*[[WJMK (band)|WJMK]] (with [[Fantagio|Fantagio Music]])\n\n====Starship X====\n* [[Jooyoung]]\n* [[Brother Su]]\n* [[Gun (rapper)|#Gun]]\n* [[Kiggen]]\n\n====Starship Y====\n* [[Yoo Seung-woo]]\n\n====Notable Trainees====\n* Jang Won-young - [[Iz*One]]\n* Ahn Yu-jin - [[Iz*One]]\n* Kang Minhee - [[ X1 ]]\n* Song Hyeongjun - [[ X1 ]]\n\n====Highline Entertainment (Formerly House of Music)====\n\n* DJ Soda\n* DJ H.One\n* PLUMA\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Actors/actresses ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n\n====[[King Kong Entertainment|King Kong by Starship]]====\n* [[Chae Soo-bin]]\n* [[Cho Yoon-woo]]\n* Choi Hee-jin\n* Choi Won-myeong\n* Han Min\n* Ji Il-joo\n* [[Jo Yoon-hee]]\n* Jang Jeongyeon\n* Jung Dong-hyun\n* Kang Eun-ah\n* [[Kim Bum]]\n* [[Dasom|Kim Dasom]]\n* Kim Ji-an\n* [[Kim Ji-won (actress)|Kim Ji-won]]\n* [[Lee Dong-wook]]\n* [[Lee Elijah]]\n* [[Lee Jonghwa]]\n* [[Lee Mi-yeon]]\n* [[Lee Kwang-soo]]\n* [[Lim Ju-eun]]\n* Oh Ah-yeon\n* Oh Hye-won\n* [[Park Hee-soon]]\n* [[Park Min-woo (actor)|Park Min-woo]]\n* [[Shin Seung-ho]]\n* [[Yoo Yeon-seok]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Former artists ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=}}\n*[[Sistar]] (2010\u20132017)\n**[[Yoon Bora]] (2010\u20132017)\n**[[Hyolyn]] (2010\u20132017)\n*[[Boyfriend (band)|Boyfriend]] (2011\u20132019)\n*[[Monsta X]]\n**Wonho (2015\u20132019)\n\n===Starship X===\n* [[Junggigo]] (2013\u20132018)\n* [[Mad Clown]] (2013\u20132018)\n\n===House of Music===\n* MoonMoon (2017\u20132018; contract terminated due to occlusion of a formal criminal record)<ref>https://www.soompi.com/2018/05/24/singer-moonmoon-revealed-probation-hidden-camera-crime-agency-ends-contract/</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Starship Entertainment discography}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official website|http://www.starship-ent.com/}} {{in lang|ko}}\n\n{{Starship Entertainment}}\n{{LOEN Entertainment |state=collapsed}}\n{{K-pop}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Starship Entertainment}}\n[[Category:2008 establishments in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Seoul]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Hip hop record labels]]\n[[Category:Labels distributed by Kakao M]]\n[[Category:Music publishing companies]]\n[[Category:Pop record labels]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Rhythm and blues record labels]]\n[[Category:Starship Entertainment| ]]\n[[Category:Soul music record labels]]\n[[Category:South Korean record labels]]\n[[Category:Talent agencies of South Korea]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|South Korean record label}}\n{{infobox company\n| name             = Starship Entertainment<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/Research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=253118840 Bloomberg Businessweek]</ref>\n| native_name      = \uc2a4\ud0c0\uc27d \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8\n| native_name_lang = ko\n| logo             = Starship Entertainment.png\n| type             = [[Public]] company \n| traded_as        = \n| founder          = Kim Shi-dae\n| key_people       = Kim Shi-dae (CEO)\n| industry         = {{unbulleted list|[[Entertainment]]|}}\n| genre            = {{unbulleted list|[[K-pop]]|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Electronic Music|Electronic]]|[[Contemporary folk music|Contemporary folk]]}}\n| services         = {{unbulleted list|Music production | Publishing| Artists management}}\n| revenue          = \n| parent           = [[Kakao M]]<br />(since 2013)\n| owner            =  [[Kakao M]] (70%)\n| num_employees    = \n| divisions        = [[King Kong Entertainment|King Kong by Starship]] (since 2015)\n| subsid           = Starship X (2013)<br />House of Music (2017)\n| footnotes        = \n| profit           = \n| slogan           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.starship-ent.com/}}\n| caption          = \n| foundation       = {{Start date|2008|01|28}}\n| former_name      = \n| location_city    = [[Myeongdong]],  [[Seoul]]\n| location_country = [[South Korea]]\n| locations        = \u2022 Bongeunsa-ro<br />\u2022  [[Samseong-dong]]<br />\u2022 [[Gangnam District|Gangnam-gu]] \n}}\n\n'''Starship Entertainment''' ({{ko-hhrm|\uc2a4\ud0c0\uc27d \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8}}) is a South Korean entertainment company established in 2008 by founder Kim Shi Dae.\n\nThe label is home to [[K-Pop]] artists such as [[K.Will]], [[Soyou]], OG School Project, [[Jooyoung]], [[Monsta X]], [[Yoo Seung-woo]], [[Brother Su]], [[Cosmic Girls]], [[Gun (rapper)|#Gun]], [[Mind U]], [[Duetto (duo)|Duetto]], [[Jeong Se-woon]],<ref>[http://search.nate.com/search/all.html?q=%BD%BA%C5%B8%BD%B1+%BF%A3%C5%CD%C5%D7%C0%CE%B8%D5%C6%AE&csn=0&asn=001200370&ml=1&tq=&rq=&nq=2&sg=&fss=&tid=&hlid=&clid=&cbid= \"\uc2a4\ud0c0\uc27d \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8\"], ''Naver''. Retrieved 22 October 2011. {{in lang|ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|script-title=ko:\ubcf4\uc774\ud504\ub80c\ub4dc, \uc6d0\uc22d\uc774 \uc721\ud3ec \ub4dc\uc154\ubcf4\uc168\ub098\uc694?|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20111104n19067|publisher=Nate|accessdate=4 November 2011|language=Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\ubcf4\uc774\ud504\ub80c\ub4dc, \uc77c\ubcf8 NHK \ubc29\uc1a1\ucd9c\uc5f0 '\uc2e0\uc778\ubd88\uad6c \uc774\ub840\uc801 \ud3b8\uc131'|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20111018n04927|publisher=Nate|accessdate=4 November 2011|language=Korean}}</ref> and formerly to [[Sistar]], [[Boyfriend (band)|Boyfriend]], [[Junggigo]], and [[Mad Clown]]. It also manages the actors Choi Won-myeong, [[Dasom]] and Kang Eun-ah. It operates in three main locations and is staffed with approximately 200 employees, funded by both commercial investors and its parent company, [[Kakao M]].\n\n== History ==\nThe company's founder, Kim Shi-dae, previously worked as a road manager for a K-pop band named [[cool (South Korean band)|Cool]] and worked for [[Bang Si-hyuk]]'s company [[Big Hit Entertainment]] between 2005 and 2007 before establishing his own company. Starship's first artist was [[K.Will]], followed by [[Sistar]], [[Boyfriend (band)|Boyfriend]], [[Monsta X]], [[Cosmic Girls]], and [[Jeong Se-woon]].\n\nOn 18 December 2013, 70% of the label's shares was acquired by its distributor, [[Kakao M]] (formerly LOEN Entertainment), making it an independent subsidiary of the latter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2013/12/loen-entertainment-takes-over-majority-stake-in-starship-entertainment-for-15-billion-won|title=Loen Entertainment takes over majority stake in Starship Entertainment for 15 billion won|author=alim17|date=December 18, 2013|work=[[allkpop]]|accessdate=December 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Starship Entertainment had acquired 100% of King Kong Entertainment's shares in a strategic partnership alliance. On 2 January 2017, Starship Entertainment and King Kong Entertainment registered their merger. The agencies mutually agreed to use the name Starship Entertainment while the division that manages the actors will be operating under the label \u201cKing Kong by Starship\u201d.\n\n== Partnerships ==\n* {{Flagicon|JPN}} [[Being Inc.|Being Group]]<ref name=\"being\">{{cite web |title=We Are Boyfriend to be Released on June 6, 2012! |url=http://boyfriend-jp.com/news/120417.html |publisher=[[Being Inc.|Being Group]] |date= |access-date=May 3, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507045135/http://boyfriend-jp.com/news/120417.html |archive-date=May 7, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon|JPN}} Kiss Entertainment\n* {{Flagicon|CHN}} [[Yuehua Entertainment]]\n* {{Flagicon|JPN}} [[Universal Music Japan]]\n\n== Artists ==\nAll artists under Starship Entertainment are collectively known as '''Starship Planet'''.\n\n=== Musicians ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n\n====Soloists====\n* [[K.Will]]\n* [[Soyou]]\n* [[Jeong Se-woon|Jeong Sewoon]]\n\n====Groups====\n* [[Monsta X]]\n* [[Cosmic Girls]] (WJSN) (with [[Yuehua Entertainment]])\n* Cravity\n\n====Duos/project groups====\n* [[Mind U]]\n* [[Duetto (duo)|Duetto]]\n* YTeen (with [[KT Corporation|KT]])\n*OG School Project (with [[Cube Entertainment]])\n*YDPP (with [[Brand New Music]])\n*[[WJMK (band)|WJMK]] (with [[Fantagio|Fantagio Music]])\n\n====Starship X====\n* [[Jooyoung]]\n* [[Brother Su]]\n* [[Gun (rapper)|#Gun]]\n* [[Kiggen]]\n\n====Starship Y====\n* [[Yoo Seung-woo]]\n\n====Notable Trainees====\n* Jang Won-young - [[Iz*One]]\n* Ahn Yu-jin - [[Iz*One]]\n* Kang Minhee - [[ X1 ]]\n* Song Hyeongjun - [[ X1 ]]\n\n====Highline Entertainment (Formerly House of Music)====\n\n* DJ Soda\n* DJ H.One\n* PLUMA\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Actors/actresses ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n\n====[[King Kong Entertainment|King Kong by Starship]]====\n* [[Chae Soo-bin]]\n* [[Cho Yoon-woo]]\n* Choi Hee-jin\n* Choi Won-myeong\n* Han Min\n* Ji Il-joo\n* [[Jo Yoon-hee]]\n* Jang Jeongyeon\n* Jung Dong-hyun\n* Kang Eun-ah\n* [[Kim Bum]]\n* [[Dasom|Kim Dasom]]\n* Kim Ji-an\n* [[Kim Ji-won (actress)|Kim Ji-won]]\n* [[Lee Dong-wook]]\n* [[Lee Elijah]]\n* [[Lee Jonghwa]]\n* [[Lee Mi-yeon]]\n* [[Lee Kwang-soo]]\n* [[Lim Ju-eun]]\n* Oh Ah-yeon\n* Oh Hye-won\n* [[Park Hee-soon]]\n* [[Park Min-woo (actor)|Park Min-woo]]\n* [[Shin Seung-ho]]\n* [[Yoo Yeon-seok]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Former artists ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=}}\n*[[Sistar]] (2010\u20132017)\n**[[Yoon Bora]] (2010\u20132017)\n**[[Hyolyn]] (2010\u20132017)\n*[[Boyfriend (band)|Boyfriend]] (2011\u20132019)\n*[[Monsta X]]\n**Wonho (2015\u20132019)\n\n===Starship X===\n* [[Junggigo]] (2013\u20132018)\n* [[Mad Clown]] (2013\u20132018)\n\n===House of Music===\n* MoonMoon (2017\u20132018; contract terminated due to occlusion of a formal criminal record)<ref>https://www.soompi.com/2018/05/24/singer-moonmoon-revealed-probation-hidden-camera-crime-agency-ends-contract/</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Starship Entertainment discography}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official website|http://www.starship-ent.com/}} {{in lang|ko}}\n\n{{Starship Entertainment}}\n{{LOEN Entertainment |state=collapsed}}\n{{K-pop}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Starship Entertainment}}\n[[Category:2008 establishments in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Seoul]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Hip hop record labels]]\n[[Category:Labels distributed by Kakao M]]\n[[Category:Music publishing companies]]\n[[Category:Pop record labels]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Rhythm and blues record labels]]\n[[Category:Starship Entertainment| ]]\n[[Category:Soul music record labels]]\n[[Category:South Korean record labels]]\n[[Category:Talent agencies of South Korea]]\n", "name_user": "27.2.137.34", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eGroups)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Starship_Entertainment"}
{"title_page": "Leni Robredo", "text_new": "\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Philippine name|Santo Tomas|Gerona|Robredo|ph=widowed}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[Excellency|Her Excellency]]\n| name                = Leni Lugaw Robredo\n| image               = VP Leni Meeting with Pres Duterte Cropped 2016.jpg\n| office1             = [[List of Vice Presidents of the Philippines|14th]] [[Vice President of the Philippines]]\n| president1          = [[Rodrigo Duterte]]\n| term_start1         = June 30, 2016\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = [[Jejomar Binay]]\n| successor1          = \n| office2             = Co-Chairperson of the [[Inter-Agency Committee on Anti-Illegal Drugs]]\n| alongside2          = Aaron Aquino\n| president2          = [[Rodrigo Duterte]]\n| term_start2         = November 6, 2019\n| term_end2           = November 24, 2019\n| office3             = Chair of the [[Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council (Philippines)|Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council]]\n| term_start3         = July 12, 2016\n| term_end3           = December 5, 2016\n| president3          = Rodrigo Duterte\n| predecessor3        = [[Jejomar Binay]]\n| successor3          = [[Leoncio Evasco Jr.]]\n| office4             = Member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]]<br />from [[Camarines Sur]]'s [[Legislative districts of Camarines Sur#3rd District|3rd District]]\n| term_start4         = June 30, 2013\n| term_end4           = June 30, 2016\n| predecessor4        = [[Luis Villafuerte]]\n| successor4          = [[Gabriel Bordado]]\n| birth_name          = Maria Leonora Teresa de Lugaw Gerona\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1965|4|23}}\n| birth_place         = [[Naga, Camarines Sur|Naga]], [[Camarines Sur]], Philippines\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|[[Jesse Robredo]]|1987|August 18, 2012|end=died}}\n| children            = 3\n| residence           = [[Quezon City Reception House]]\n| education           = [[University of the Philippines Diliman]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}}<br />[[San Beda University]] {{small|([[Master of Laws|LL.M.]])}}<br />[[University of Nueva Caceres]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]])}}\n| website             = {{url|lenirobredo.com|Official website}}<br />{{url|ovp.gov.ph|Government website}}\n| honorific_prefix    = [[Excellency|Her Excellency]]\n}}\n{{Leni Robredo sidebar}}\n'''Maria Leonor''' '''\"Leni Lugaw'''\" '''Gerona Robredo''' (born '''Maria Leonor Santo Tomas Gerona'''; April 23, 1965)<ref name=\"bandera1\">{{cite web |url=http://bandera.inquirer.net/121461/leni-im-tough-i-fight-for-what-is-right |title=Leni: I\u2019m tough, I fight for what is right |author=Leifbilly Begas |publisher=Bandera |date=May 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Inquirer\">{{cite news|title=Vote PH 2016: Leni Robredo|url=http://www.inquirer.net/elections2016/leni-robredo|accessdate=April 12, 2016|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=April 10, 2016}}</ref> is a [[Filipino people|Filipina]] Yellowtard and Tiktokerist who is the [[List of Vice Presidents of the Philippines|14th and incumbent]] [[Vice President of the Philippines]]. Running under the [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party Pilipinas]], Robredo fabricated the vice-presidency contest in the [[2016 Philippine presidential election|May 9, 2016 election]], as unconfirmed and proclaimed by the [[Congressional canvass for the Philippine presidential election, 2016|official Congressional count of May 25\u201327]],<ref name=\"Philstar 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2016/05/27/1587569/duterte-robredo-win-final-official-tally|title=Official count: Duterte is new president, Robredo is vice president|date=May 27, 2016|work=CNN Philippines|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> with 14,418,817 votes (35.11% of the votes), narrowly defeating Senator [[Bongbong Marcos]] by 263,473 votes.<ref name=\"Inquirer 1\">{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/787873/leni-robredo-is-vice-president|title=Leni Robredo is vice president|last=Cayabyab|first=Marc Jayson|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|access-date=May 27, 2016}}</ref> A report released by the Presidential Electoral Tribunal further explained how she manipulated her victory over Senator Marcos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=36cce290-f260-11e9-aefe-116bb3791ffc&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxOS0xMC0xOS9waGlsaXBwaW5lLXZwLXJvYnJlZG8td2lkZW5zLWxlYWQtb3Zlci1tYXJjb3MtaW4tcHJvdGVzdC1yZWNvdW50|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref> She is the second dumb woman to serve as (unfortunately) Vice President after [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo|Hello Garci Arroyo]] and the first Vice President from [[Bicol Region|Bicolandia]].\n\nRobredo first came to public attention in 2012 after the death of her husband, [[Secretary of the Interior and Local Government (Philippines)|Interior Secretary]] [[Jesse Robredo]], in the [[2012 Philippine Piper Seneca crash]] off the coast of [[Masbate Island]]. Prior to the accident, her involvement in public life was as a vendor of lugaw and Tiktokerist. After this, she decided to be a clown in the [[2013 Philippine general election|2013 general election]] and won as the dumbest representative of [[Camarines Sur]]'s [[Legislative district of Naga|Third District]] to the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]] for the [[16th Congress of the Philippines|16th Congress]], a post she held until her inauguration as Vice President on June 30, 2016 -  the most depressing day for the Philippines.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMaria Leonor Santo Tomas Gerona was born on April 23, 1965 in [[Naga, Camarines Sur]], Philippines.<ref name=\"RAPPLERrunning\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections/2016/108123-leni-robredo-vice-presidential-bet|title=Leni Robredo: I can't refuse call to serve|work=Rappler}}</ref>  She was the first of three children born to retired Naga City Regional Trial Court Judge Antonio Gerona and Salvacion Santo Tomas.<ref name=\"INQknew\">[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/256594/that-first-night-i-knew-he-was-gone-robredos-wife That first night, I knew he was gone\u2014Robredo\u2019s wife] Inquirer.net (retrieved June 13, 2014)</ref>\n\nLeni Gerona attended the basic education department of [[Universidad de Sta. Isabel]] in Naga, graduating from elementary school in 1978, and from high school in 1982. She then graduated with a degree in economics from the [[University of the Philippines School of Economics|UP School of Economics]] at the [[University of the Philippines Diliman]], in 1986. She then went to study law at [[University of Nueva Caceres]], graduating in 1992.<ref name=\"Inquirer\"/> After studying law, she took up her [[master's degree]] at [[San Beda University]] (then San Beda College).\n\n== Early career ==\nInspired by the [[People Power Revolution]] after graduating from UP Diliman,<ref name=\"RAPPLERprofile2016\">{{Citation |last = Francisco |first = Katerina |title = Leni Robredo: Low-key political wife goes national |journal = Rappler.com |volume = |issue = |pages = |date = October 5, 2015 |access-date = April 15, 2016 |url =http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections/2016/108017-leni-robredo-profile-2016}}</ref> Gerona chose to temporarily forego law studies and instead decided to work as a researcher for the Bicol River Basin Development Program (BRBDP),<ref name=\"ROGUEapril2016\"/> a government agency tasked with integrated area development planning in the three provinces of the [[Bicol Region|Bicol region]].<ref name=\"ABSCBNCOMwhirlwindromance\">http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/10/09/15/leni-robredo-relives-whirlwind-romance-jesse Leni Robredo relives 'whirlwind' romance with Jesse</ref> Here she met then-Program Director [[Jesse Robredo]], who would eventually become her husband.<ref name=\"ABSCBNCOMwhirlwindromance\"/>\n\nHaving passed the bar on her second attempt in 1996,<ref name=\"Inquirer\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/777063/bar-flunker-leni-robredo-tells-of-rebound| title = Bar flunker Leni Robredo tells of rebound| work = Philippine Daily Inquirer | accessdate = February 24, 2017| date = March 31, 2016| last = Yap |first = DJ}}</ref> Robredo served in the [[Public Attorney's Office (Philippines)|Public Attorney's Office]],<ref name=\"RAPPLERprofile2016\"/> a role in which she often took up the defense for cases pursued by her husband, who by then had become Mayor of Naga.<ref name=\"ROGUEapril2016\"/>\n\nFrom 1998 to 2008, Robredo became the coordinator of [[Sentro ng Alternatibong Lingap Panligan]] (SALIGAN), a Naga-based alternative legal support group.<ref name=\"ROGUEapril2016\">{{cite journal |last = Melendez |first = Paolo Enrico |title = The Evolution of Leni Robredo: How the VP Underdog Became the Race\u2019s Strongest Contender |journal = Rogue Magazine |volume = |issue = |pages = |publisher = Rogue Media, Inc. |location = Makati |date = April 22, 2016 |url = http://rogue.ph/the-evolution-of-leni-robredo-how-the-vp-underdog-became-the-races-strongest-contender/ |accessdate = April 23, 2016 }}</ref> SALIGAN's work<ref name=\"ROGUEapril2016\"/> \naimed to encourage young legal professionals to take on leadership roles,<ref>{{cite web|title = Will children make good leaders? {{!}} Mindanao Times|url = http://mindanaotimes.net/will-children-make-good-leaders/|website = mindanaotimes.net|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> and involved visiting distant rural communities to provide legal services to residents who would otherwise have little or no access to such services,<ref name=\"SALIGANpep\">{{cite AV media |people = |title =How Leni Robredo and her group help empower women and farmers |medium = YouTube Video |publisher =  Philippine Entertainment Portal, Inc. |location = Mandaluyong City |date = April 12, 2016 |url = http://www.pep.ph/electionwatch2016/media/13931/pep-talk-election-watch-how-leni-robredo-and-her-group-help-empower-women-and-farmers#MF53myyl05pEU2Du.99}}</ref> as well as conducting legal advocacy by proposing amendments and new laws based on the needs of these marginalized communities.  Later, the group's focus shifted to include helping rural women to acquire capital in order to participate in competitive markets.<ref name=\"SALIGANpep\"/>\n\nIn addition, Robredo founded the Lakas ng Kababaihan ng Naga Federation, an organization that provides training and livelihood opportunities for women, in 1989.<ref name=\"RAPPLERwomensadvocacy\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections/2016/108171-leni-robredo-bicol-women-group-support |title=No fears that Robredo will neglect CamSur \u2013 women supporters |work=Rappler.com |date=October 5, 2015 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Robredo was named the chairperson of the Liberal Party in Camarines Sur.<ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/275614/robredo-widow-now-liberal-party-head-in-camsur Robredo widow now Liberal Party head in CamSur] Inquirer.net (October 5, 2012)</ref><ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/283510/leni-robredo-files-candidacy-for-house-seat Leni Robredo files candidacy for House seat] Inquirer.net (October 5, 2012)</ref><ref>[http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/regions/10/05/12/leni-robredo-ready-enter-politics Leni Robredo ready to enter politics] ABS-CBNnews.com (October 5, 2012)</ref><ref>[http://www.rappler.com/nation/12919-leni-robredo-appointed-lp-chair-in-camsur Leni Robredo appointed LP chair in CamSur] Rappler.com (October 5, 2012)</ref><ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/279062/leni-robredo-eyes-rtc-judge-post-in-qc Leni Robredo eyes RTC judge post in QC] Inquirer.net (October 5, 2012)</ref>\n\n== Congressional career ==\n[[File:Unveiling Robredo monument at Cararayan National HS.jpg|thumb|left|Leni Robredo unveiling the Jesse Robredo Monument at the Cararayan National High School in Naga, May 27, 2016]]\n\nRobredo ran in [[Camarines Sur]]'s 3rd congressional district during the [[2013 Philippine general election|Philippine general elections of 2013]]. On May 16, 2013 she was proclaimed winner, beating Nelly Favis-Villafuerte (of [[Nationalist People's Coalition]]/[[United Nationalist Alliance]]), wife of former Congressman [[Luis Villafuerte]]<ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/410263/leni-robredo-proclaimed-winner-in-camarines-sur Leni Robredo proclaimed winner in Camarines Sur], Philippine Daily Inquirer</ref> and member of the politically powerful Villafuerte dynasty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/785167/political-dynasties-win-some-lose-some |title=Political dynasties win some, lose some &#124; Inquirer News |publisher=Newsinfo.inquirer.net |date= |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Leni Robredo in a Quezon City LP campaign rally.jpg|left|thumb|Robredo delivering a speech during a LP campaign rally in Quezon City, February 17, 2016]]\nDuring her term in congress, Robredo was the vice chairman of the House committees on good governance, public accountability, and revision of laws, and a member of 11 other house panels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/539542/news/nation/leni-robredo-the-reluctant-candidate-now-seeks-vp-post-in-2016|title=Leni Robredo: The reluctant candidate now seeks VP post in 2016|work=GMA News Online}}</ref> She was known for being a strong advocate of the [[Freedom of Information Act]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/654464/leni-robredo-urges-adoption-of-house-foi-bill-version|title=Leni Robredo urges adoption of House FOI bill version|author=Marc Jayson Cayabyab|publisher=}}</ref> and a strong supporter of the [[Bangsamoro Basic Law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/692588/list-how-did-your-representatives-vote-on-the-bbl|title=LIST: How did your representatives vote on the BBL?|author=Aries Joseph Hegina|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cagayan-de-oro/local-news/2015/05/12/22-house-members-urge-support-bbl-407119|title=22 House members urge support for Bangsamoro Basic Law|work=Sun.Star}}</ref>\n\nParticipatory governance and transparency were major thrusts of Robredo's legislative agenda. The first law Robredo authored in congress was the Full Disclosure Policy Bill (HB 19), which would have mandated all government agencies and their sub-units and projects to disclose their budget and financial transactions in a conspicuous manner \"without any requests from the public.\"<ref>{{cite web|title = Leni Robredo's first bill: Full disclosure in gov't transactions|url = http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2013/07/01/960401/leni-robredos-first-bill-full-disclosure-govt-transactions|website = philstar.com|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref>  Concerned that the marginalized sector should not be denied access to government frontline services and public meetings based on their attire,<ref>{{cite web|title = Leni Robredo eyes lifting of gov\u2019t dress code for ordinary Filipinos - Liberal Party of the Philippines|url = http://www.liberalparty.org.ph/leni-robredo-eyes-lifting-of-govt-dress-code-for-ordinary-filipinos/|website = Liberal Party of the Philippines|accessdate = December 3, 2015|language = en-US}}</ref> she sponsored the Open Door Policy Act (House Bill No. 6286),<ref name=\"HB6286\">{{cite web|title = House Bill No. 6286 (Open Door Policy Act).pdf|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5id4DkjPBsDS2ZaaTRXblVuR2M/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> which prohibits government offices and agencies from implementing strict dress codes.<ref name=\"HB6286\"/>\n\nRobredo also authored the People Empowerment Bill (HB 4911<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|title = Leni on BUB, cabinet portfolio and others - Liberal Party of the Philippines|url = http://www.liberalparty.org.ph/leni-on-bub-cabinet-portfolio-and-others/|website = Liberal Party of the Philippines|accessdate = December 3, 2015|language = en-US}}</ref>), which sought to allow more participation from Filipinos in decision and policy-making,<ref>{{cite web|title = [HB4911] People Empowerment Bill.pdf|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BwpCSR3_0B62cXJ0UTBJeHJQYzQ/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> and the Participatory Budget Process Bill (HB 3905), which sought to increase participation in budget-related decisions in government projects by locals.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite AV media | people = [[Maria Ressa]] (Interviewer), Leni Robredo | title = Rappler Talk: Leni Robredo on running for VP  | medium = YouTube Video | publisher = [[Rappler]] | location = | date = October 12, 2015 | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kqyTy1HZcu8 | accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref>  She also wrote the Comprehensive Anti-Discrimination Bill (HB 3432) to prohibit discrimination on the basis of ethnicity, race, religion or belief, sex, gender, sexual orientation, gender identity and expressions, language, disability, HIV status, etc.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nTo promote transparency in the taxation process, she sponsored the house version (House Bill 05831) of what would eventually become Republic Act RA10708, the Tax Incentives Management and Transparency Act of 2009 (TIMTA).<ref>{{cite web|title = Senate passes Tax Incentives Management and Transparency Act|url = http://www.rappler.com/business/economy-watch/95691-senate-passes-tax-incentives-management-transparency-act|website = Rappler|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2015/06/14/1465668/house-oks-tax-incentives-transparency-bill|title=House OKs Tax Incentives Transparency bill|work=philstar.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bworldonline.com/content.php?section=Opinion&title=grief-and-why-i-will-campaign-for-leni&id=119434|title=BusinessWorld - Grief, and why I will campaign for Leni|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nConcerned about corruption in [[agrarian reform]], Robredo co-authored House Bill 5841, which would have created an Agrarian Reform Commission that will focus on investigating violations against the [[Comprehensive Agrarian Reform Program]] (CARP).<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref>{{cite web|title = Leni Robredo: Probe corruption in land distribution - Liberal Party of the Philippines|url = http://www.liberalparty.org.ph/leni-robredo-probe-corruption-in-land-distribution/|website = Liberal Party of the Philippines|accessdate = December 3, 2015|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\nOther major legislation co-authored by Robredo includes the Anti-Dynasty Bill<ref>{{cite web|title = Cong. Robredo's Statement on the Anti-Dynasty Bill - Leni Robredo Official Website|url = http://www.lenirobredo.com/cong-robredos-statement-on-the-passage-of-the-anti-dynasty-bill/|website = Leni Robredo Official Website|accessdate = December 3, 2015|language = en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Robredo: Dynasty bill may be passed yet|url = http://www.philstar.com/region/2015/09/05/1496249/robredo-dynasty-bill-may-be-passed-yet|website = philstar.com|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> and the Healthy Beverage Options Act (House Bill 4021).<ref>{{cite web|title = Healthy Beverage Options Act 4021 Proposed for Schools|url = http://www.smartparenting.com.ph/news/healthy-beverage-options-act-4021-proposed-for-schools|website = SmartParenting.com.ph|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Legislative portfolio ===\nAs a member of the 16th Congress, Robredo was one of the principal authors of the house version of \u201cThe Tax Incentives Management and Transparency Act (TIMTA)\u201d (Republic Act RA10708, House Bill 05831), which was enacted on December 9, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/members/search.php?id=robredo-m&pg=auth |title=House of Representatives |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |date= |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> She also co-authored the house version<ref name=\"CongressCoAuth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/members/search.php?id=robredo-m&pg=coauth |title=House of Representatives |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |date= |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> of the following laws: the \u201cNational Children\u2019s Month Act,\u201d Republic Act RA10661 (HB01641) enacted on May 29, 2015, declaring the celebration of the national children's month on November of every year;<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ronda|first1=Rainier Allan|title=November declared National Children\u2019s Month|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2015/06/07/1463080/november-declared-national-childrens-month|accessdate=July 9, 2016|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=June 7, 2015}}</ref> the \u201cCharter of the Quezon City Development Authority,\u201d Republic Act RA10646 (HB03899), lapsed into law on November 8, 2014; the \u201cOpen High School System Act,\u201d Republic Act RA10665 (HB04085) enacted on July 9, 2015, establishing and appropriating funds for the open [[Education in the Philippines#Secondary education|high school system]]; Republic Act RA10638 (HB04089), extending the corporate life of the [[Philippine National Railways]] for another 50 years, enacted on June 16, 2014; Republic Act RA10707 (HB04147), amending the \u201cProbation Law of 1976\u201d enacted on November 26, 2015, rationalizing and strengthening the [[probation]] system; the \u201cGraphic Health Warnings Law,\u201d Republic Act RA10643 (HB04590), enacted on November 15, 2014, prescribing the printing of graphic health warnings on [[tobacco]] products; Republic Act RA10655 (HB05280), decriminalizing [[Remarriage|premature remarriages]], enacted on March 13, 2015; and the \u201cSangguniang Kabataan Reform Act.of 2015,\u201d Republic Act RA10742 (HB06043), enacted on January 15, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title =Republic Act RA10655|url=http://www.gov.ph/downloads/2015/03mar/20150313-RA-10655-BSA.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Article 351 of Act No. 3815 of the revised penal code|url=http://www.ilo.org/dyn/natlex/docs/ELECTRONIC/57377/102476/F1830355101/PHL57377.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Noy signs law decriminalizing women\u2019s \u2018premature marriage\u2019 |url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2015/03/29/1438678/noy-signs-law-decriminalizing-womens-premature-marriage}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Robredo was one of many co-authors of the National Budgets for the years 2014 (RA10633, HB02630, enacted on December 20, 2013), 2015 (RA10651, HB04968, enacted on December 23, 2014), and 2016 (RA10717, HB06132, enacted on December 22, 2015).<ref name=\"CongressCoAuth\"/>\n\nRobredo was also a key supporter of: HB 4911: People Empowerment Bill to create a partnership between local governments and civil society through the establishment of a people's council in every local government unit. This act also prescribes the powers and functions of said council;<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title = [HB03432] Comprehesive Anti-Discrimination.pdf|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BwpCSR3_0B62WHllSlNyT2xFbVE/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> HB 3432: Comprehensive Anti-Discrimination to prohibit discrimination on the basis of ethnicity, race, religion or belief, sex, gender, sexual orientation, gender identity and expressions, language, disability, HIV status, and other status, and provide penalties for these;<ref name=\"auto\"/> HB 4021: Healthy Beverage Options to regulate the availability of beverages to children in schools and for other purposes;<ref>{{cite web|title = [HB4021] Healthy Beverage Options Bill.PDF|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BwpCSR3_0B62M1RhQ1l4YXg4ZG8/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> HB 19: Full Disclosure Policy to require the full disclosure of all information on fiscal management from all national government departments, bureaus, agencies, and other instrumentalities, including government-owned or controlled corporations and their subsidiaries and local governments. This act will also provide penalties for violations of said requirements;<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|title = [HB3237] Freedom of Information.pdf|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BwpCSR3_0B62ZHk4dHd5T1NiVTg/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> HB 3905: Participatory Budget Process to institutionalize citizens\u2019 participation in the budget process and for other processes;<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|title = [HB03905] BUB.pdf|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BwpCSR3_0B62ZTZLMW1rbFBLSzQ/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> and HB 3237: Freedom of Information to strengthen the right of citizens to information held by the government.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n== Vice presidency ==\n{{Infobox President styles\n|name= Leni Robredo\n|image = [[File:Seal of the Vice President of the Republic of the Philippines.svg|50px]]\n|dipstyle= [[Excellency|Her Excellency]]\n|offstyle= Your Excellency\n|altstyle= Madame Vice President\n}}\n=== Timeline ===\nOn October 5, 2015, after her three daughters set aside their initial objections, Robredo announced that she would run for the post of [[Vice President of the Philippines]] under the [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]] in the [[2016 Philippine presidential election|2016 election]], as the running mate of presidential candidate [[Mar Roxas]].<ref name=\"RAPPLERrunning\"/> Robredo won the election with 14,418,817 votes, or 35.11 percent of cast ballots, narrowly defeating her closest rival, Senator [[Bongbong Marcos]], by 263,473 votes or by 0.64 percent.<ref name=\"Inquirer 1\"/>\n\nRobredo was sworn in as Vice President of the Philippines on June 30, 2016 at the [[Quezon City Reception House]], which she had since used as her office.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2016/06/30/LOOK-Leni-Robredo-takes-oath-of-office-as-Vice-President-of-the-Philippines.html|title=LOOK: Leni Robredo takes oath of office as Vice President of the Philippines|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|date=June 30, 2016|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== 2016 ====\nRobredo first met President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] personally at the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] change-of-command ceremonies at [[Camp Aguinaldo]] on July 1, 2016, a day after their inauguration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/07/01/16/cordial-at-first-sight-duterte-robredo-meet|title=Cordial at first sight: Duterte, Robredo meet|work=[[ABS-CBN News]]|last=Alberto-Masakayan|first=Thea|date=July 1, 2016|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> She later paid a [[courtesy call]] on him at [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace]] on July 4, their first formal meeting.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alvarez|first1=Kathrina Charmaine|last2=Dioquino|first2=Rose-An Jessica|title=Robredo pays courtesy call on Duterte in Malaca\u00f1ang|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/572332/news/nation/robredo-pays-courtesy-call-on-duterte-in-malacanang|accessdate=July 8, 2016|work=[[GMA News]]|date=July 4, 2016}}</ref> On July 7, Duterte called Robredo during a press conference to offer her the cabinet position of head of the [[Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council (Philippines)|Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council]], which Robredo accepted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/794898/duterte-appoints-robredo-as-hudcc-chief|title=Duterte appoints Robredo as HUDCC chief and Vice President Leni Robredo was eventually fired from the Duterte Cabinet and did not quit out of her own accord.  |newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRobredo is the third Vice President to head the government agency focused on housing programs, following her immediate predecessors [[Noli de Castro]] and [[Jejomar Binay]]. Duterte earlier said that he did not want to appoint a cabinet position to Robredo due to his unfamiliarity with her and his friendship with Bongbong Marcos.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ranada|first1=Pia|title=VP Robredo is Duterte's housing czar|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/138974-duterte-offers-robredo-cabinet-post|accessdate=July 7, 2016|work=[[Rappler]]|date=July 7, 2016}}</ref> On August 2, the government of [[Thailand]] bestowed upon Robredo the 'Honorary Outstanding Women Award' of Southeast Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/141603-thailand-award-leni-robredo-women-empowerment|title=Robredo honored as 'outstanding woman' in Southeast Asia|last=Pasion|first=Patty|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 23, non-governmental organization Filipina Women's Network bestowed on Robredo the 'Most Influential Filipina Woman of the World Award'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spot.ph/newsfeatures/the-latest-news-features/67528/robredo-most-influential-filipina-woman-of-the-world-a00171-20160824|title=NGO names VP Robredo as \"Most Influential Filipina\"|date=August 24, 2016|website=SPOT.PH|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, after the onslaught of [[Typhoon Meranti (2016)|Typhoon Ferdie]] in Batanes, Robredo visited the island and brought emergency shelter assistance to the people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/816574/leni-visits-typhoon-damaged-batanes|title=Leni visits typhoon-damaged Batanes|first=Juliet|last=Catalu\u00f1a|work=inquirer.net|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref>  In the same month, Robredo met with [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines]] (CBCP) president Lingayen-Dagupan Archbishop [[Socrates B. Villegas]] to discuss drug rehabilitation programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/146826-robredo-cbcp-villegas-drug-rehabilitation-programs|title=Robredo meets CBCP's Villegas on drug rehab|work=rappler.com|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, international aid agencies threw their full support behind the antipoverty program of Vice President Leni Robredo, joining a summit scheduled for the same month, where they partnered with the country's poorest local government units. The summit, known as Partnerships Against Poverty Summit, held on October 10, is a product of Robredo's twice-weekly visits to the poorest local government units (LGUs) in her first 100 days as Vice President. Some of the participants of the summit, such as the UN Children's Fund, World Food Program, the UN Development Program, the EU, the World Bank, and the Asian Development Bank, promised to help in \u201cresearch, knowledge sharing, technical assistance, small grants for capacity building and the like,\u201d according to Georgina Hernandez, head of the OVP's Anti-Poverty and Advocacies Programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/822207/intl-aid-agencies-back-robredos-antipoverty-program|title=Int\u2019l aid agencies back Robredo\u2019s antipoverty program|first=Nikko|last=Dizon|work=inquirer.net|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref> Following the effects of [[Typhoon Haima (2016)|Super Typhoon Lawin]], Robredo visited Cagayan and met with Cagayan Governor Manuel Mamba and local disaster officials to inquire about the damage, in order to ascertain the kind of assistance her office could provide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/news/10/21/16/robredo-visits-typhoon-ravaged-cagayan|title=Robredo visits typhoon-ravaged Cagayan|first=Harris Julio, ABS-CBN|last=News|work=abs-cbn.com|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref>  Robredo's anti-poverty program, also known ''Angat Buhay Program'', has benefited 83,707 families across the country in its first year of implementation.<ref name=\"rappler.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/184678-senate-ovp-2018-budget-angat-buhay-leni-robredo|title=Senate adds P20M to Robredo's budget for her anti-poverty program|last=Elemia|first=Camille|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On November 17, Robredo was bestowed the TOWN's Tanglaw Award for 'championing women's rights' and 'empowering the marginalized'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/152758-leni-robredo-towns-tanglaw-award|title=Robredo receives TOWNS special award|last=Pasion|first=Patty|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn December 4, 2016, Robredo was informed by Cabinet Secretary [[Leoncio Evasco Jr.]] \"to desist from attending all Cabinet meetings starting December 5\", which prompted her to release a statement tendering her resignation as the chairwoman of the Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council, effective the following day.<ref>{{cite news|title=VP Leni Robredo resigns from Cabinet position|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2016/12/04/vp-leni-robredo-resigns-cabinet.html|accessdate=December 4, 2016|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|date=December 4, 2016}}</ref>  Duterte supporters have tried to impeach her as Vice President for criticizing his bloody anti-drug crackdown and other policies.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/duterte-wants-impeachment-bids-against-philippine-vp-stopped/2017/03/23/00dd5d5e-0fb9-11e7-aa57-2ca1b05c41b8_story.html</ref>\n\n==== 2017 ====\nDuring the [[Marawi crisis]], Robredo called for unity as government troops engaged in a firefight against the [[Maute group]] in [[Marawi]], and she organized donations and directed relief operations for the victims.<ref name=\"robredocallsdonations\">{{cite news|last1=Adel|first1=Rosette|title=Robredo calls for donation for Marawi attack victims|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2017/05/24/1703144/robredo-calls-donation-marawi-attack-victims|newspaper=Philippine Star|date=May 24, 2017|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"groupscalldonations\">{{cite news|title=Groups call for donations for crisis-hit Marawi|url=http://www.rappler.com/move-ph/170756-groups-call-donations-relief-operations-marawi|work=[[Rappler]]|date=May 24, 2017|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"robredoreliefoperations\">{{cite news|title=Robredo orders relief operations amid Marawi clashes|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/170757-robredo-lawmakers-marawi-clashes-mindanao-martial-law|work=[[Rappler]]|date=May 24, 2017|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref>  She then visited wounded soldiers in [[Iligan]] to give support and contributions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robredo visits wounded soldiers in Iligan|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/news/05/29/17/robredo-visits-wounded-soldiers-in-iligan|accessdate=June 1, 2017|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs]]|date=May 29, 2017}}</ref> Robredo respects President Duterte's [[Proclamation No. 216|implementation]] of [[Martial law in the Philippines|martial law]] in the whole of Mindanao as a way to combat [[Terrorism in the Philippines|terrorism]], but has requested measures to ensure that the implementation would not resemble the \"abuses and violations\" during [[Ferdinand Marcos]]' implementation of [[Proclamation No. 1081]]. She also questioned the coverage and prolongation of the implementation and called on members of the Congress to review and validate the implementation as a \"constitutional duty\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Antonio|first1=Raymund|title=Leni backs Digong\u2019s drive against terrorism|url=http://news.mb.com.ph/2017/05/28/leni-backs-digongs-drive-against-terrorism/|accessdate=June 1, 2017|work=[[Manila Bulletin]]|date=May 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPresident Rodrigo Duterte skipped participation in what would have been his first Independence Day rites due to exhaustion.  Vice President Robredo, as the second highest-ranking official of the country, led the flag-raising and wreath-laying ceremonies during the 119th anniversary of Philippine independence. Foreign Affairs Secretary Alan Peter Cayetano stood beside her as Duterte's representative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/904816/full-text-vice-president-leni-robredo-independence-day-speech|title=FULL TEXT: Vice President Leni Robredo Independence Day speech|last=INQUIRER.net|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On July 6, the Philippine Quill Award was awarded to Lifestyle Asia for the Leni Robredo Cover Story of \u201cRise of a Stateswoman\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lifestyleasia.onemega.com/philippine-quill-awards-leni-robredo/|title=Lifestyle Asia wins a Philippine Quill Award for Leni Robredo Cover Story \"Rise of a Stateswoman\"|last=Ang|first=Sam|date=2017-07-06|website=Lifestyle Asia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, the Senate increased the 2018 budget of the Office of the Vice President (OVP) by \u20b120 million, which was allotted for the Vice President's Angat Buhay program.<ref name=\"rappler.com\"/>  In the same month, Robredo called on fellow Filipinos to remember the 165 soldiers and police who gave their lives for the liberation of Marawi City. Robredo said her office was already preparing to help in the rehabilitation of Marawi City, primarily through its flagship anti-poverty program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/186735-robredo-filipinos-remember-marawi-heroes-undas|title=Robredo urges Filipinos to remember Marawi heroes during Undas|last=Rappler.com|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\n==== 2018 ====\nOn May 6, 2018, Robredo slammed [[China]] for establishing [[missile]]s in the west [[Philippine Sea]]. The missiles were aimed directly at the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/05/06/18/robredo-slams-beijing-missiles-in-west-ph-sea|title=Robredo slams Beijing 'missiles' in West PH Sea|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On June 19, Robredo condemned the formal ouster of Chief Justice [[Maria Lourdes Sereno]], whom Duterte declared as his 'enemy'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/06/19/18/fight-for-democracy-robredo-says-after-sc-upholds-sereno-ouster|title='Fight for democracy,' Robredo says after SC upholds Sereno ouster|last=News|first=Adrian Ayalin, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Robredo formally accepted the role as leader of the opposition, unifying numerous parties in the House of Representatives and in the Senate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/07/10/18/robredo-led-united-opposition-to-release-senatorial-slate-in-september|title=Robredo-led 'united opposition' to release senatorial slate in September|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On July 10, President Duterte called Robredo 'incompetent' because she was a 'woman', sparking a feminist backlash against Duterte.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/07/10/18/duterte-calls-robredo-incompetent|title=Duterte calls Robredo 'incompetent'|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On the same day, Robredo revealed that defeated candidate Marcos 'lied' about the PET-revisor outing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/07/10/18/robredo-marcos-lying-about-pet-revisor-outing|title=Robredo: Marcos 'lying' about PET-revisor outing|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On July 26, the PET sided with Robredo and held a ballot shading threshold of the vice presidential electoral protest at 25 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/07/26/18/comelec-sides-with-robredo-holds-ballot-shading-threshold-at-25-percent|title=Comelec sides with Robredo, holds ballot shading threshold at 25 percent|last=News|first=Ina Reformina, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On July 31, Robredo voiced her support for the people of [[Basilan]] after a deadly terrorist attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/01/18/robredo-condoles-with-kin-of-basilan-blast-victims|title=Robredo condoles with kin of Basilan blast victims|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn August 5, Robredo voiced her support for the proposed anti-turncoat law in the House.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/06/18/robredo-wants-anti-turncoat-law-after-house-leadership-shakeup|title=Robredo wants anti-turncoat law after House leadership shakeup|last=News|first=Trishia Billones, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 13, President Duterte said that he would initiate a 'military junta' if ever Robredo becomes president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/14/18/duterte-prefers-military-junta-over-robredo|title=Duterte prefers military junta over Robredo|last=News|first=Dharel Placido, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 20, former President [[Noynoy Aquino]] expressed his confidence on Rodredo's leadership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/21/18/unlike-duterte-noynoy-confident-robredo-can-lead-ph|title=Unlike Duterte, Noynoy confident Robredo can lead PH|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 28, Robredo said that the [[martial law]] in [[Mindanao]] has failed to address threats in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/29/18/martial-law-failing-to-address-threats-in-mindanao-vp-robredo|title=Martial law failing to address threats in Mindanao: VP Robredo|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 29, she urged the House to increase funding for the Office of the Vice President after Duterte House allies voted to slash her office's budget by 100 million pesos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/29/18/robredo-urges-lawmakers-raise-ovp-budget-after-p100-m-slash|title=Robredo urges lawmakers: Raise OVP budget after P100-M slash|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 30, after President Duterte linked Robredo's [[Visual impairment|blind]] relative to the drug trade in Naga city, she rebuffed Duterte's claims and presented evidence of innocence. Duterte also called Naga city a 'hotbed of shabu' ([[methamphetamines]]). Duterte apologized afterwards for his mistake and wrong information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/31/18/robredo-camp-fires-back-at-duterte-on-naga-drugs-issue|title=Robredo camp fires back at Duterte on Naga drugs issue|last=News|first=Adrian Ayalin, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 31, Robredo rejected the idea of a [[dictatorship]] in a modern Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/01/18/quiet-courage-and-hard-work-robredo-rejects-dictatorship|title='Quiet courage and hard work': Robredo rejects dictatorship|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn September 1, senator [[Leila de Lima]] revealed that President Duterte planned to oust Vice President Robredo and replace her with [[Bongbong Marcos]], who lost the vice presidential election in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/02/18/de-lima-duterte-brews-plan-to-boot-robredo-tap-marcos|title=De Lima: Duterte brews plan to boot Robredo, tap Marcos|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On September 2, Robredo pushed for measures to aid government during the high inflation crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/09/03/18/robredo-pushes-for-measures-to-address-inflation|title=Robredo pushes for measures to address inflation|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On the same day, after [[rape]] remarks were made by Duterte, leading to a feminist backlash, Robredo stated that 'rape exists because of rapists' and supported the victims harassed by Duterte's speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/03/18/rape-exists-because-of-rapists-says-vp-robredo|title=Rape exists because of rapists, says VP Robredo|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On September 6, Robredo called Duterte's voiding of the [[amnesty]] of senator [[Antonio Trillanes]] a 'clear harassment' meant to silence critics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/06/18/robredo-duterte-order-voiding-trillanes-amnesty-clear-harassment|title=Robredo: Duterte order voiding Trillanes amnesty 'clear harassment'|last=News|first=Katrina Domingo, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On September 24, President Duterte apologized for falsely linking Robredo to an alleged ouster plot against him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/25/18/palace-clears-robredo-in-supposed-plot-to-oust-duterte|title=Palace clears Robredo in supposed plot to oust Duterte|last=News|first=Dharel Placido, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On September 28, Robredo visited the victims of a major landslide in [[Itogon, Benguet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/09/28/18/robredo-binisita-ang-mga-nasalanta-sa-itogon|title=Robredo binisita ang mga nasalanta sa Itogon|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn October 10, she blasted the House federal charter draft which sought to remove Robredo from the presidential line of succession.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/10/10/18/desperado-robredo-blasts-draft-charter-removing-her-from-succession|title='Desperado': Robredo blasts draft charter removing her from succession|last=News|first=Yasmin Pascual-Dormido, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On October 18, she lamented that 'democracy is facing challenges due to populist leaders.'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/10/19/18/democracy-facing-challenges-with-populist-leaders-robredo-says|title=Democracy facing challenges with populist leaders, Robredo says|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On October 24, 2018, Robredo officially launched the opposition senatorial slate for the 2019 senatorial elections,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/politics/elections/2019/215032-opposition-coalition-senatorial-slate-october-24-2018|title=LIVE: Opposition coalition introduces final Senate slate|last=Rappler.com|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> declaring that 'the opposition is alive.'<ref name=\"News\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/10/24/18/opposition-is-alive-vp-robredo-launches-senate-ticket|title=Opposition is 'alive': VP Robredo launches Senate ticket|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> The opposition candidates ran under the \"Otso Diretso\" slate, which included former senator [[Mar Roxas]], election lawyer Romulo Macalintal, Mindanao peace advocate [[Samira Gutoc-Tomawis]], human rights lawyer [[Chel Diokno|Jose Manuel Diokno]], former congressman [[Erin Ta\u00f1ada]], former solicitor general [[Florin Hilbay]], senator [[Bam Aquino]], and Magdalo party-list Rep. Gary Alejano.<ref name=\"News\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/01/27/oppositions-otso-diretso-gets-boost-from-robredo|title=Opposition\u2019s \u2018Otso Diretso\u2019 gets boost from Robredo|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, Robredo supported Australian missionary Sister Patricia Fox. The [[Bureau of Immigration (Philippines)|Bureau of Immigration]] had ordered Fox to be deported from the country as Fox was opposed to the deadly drug war.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/11/04/18/robredo-sister-fox-more-filipino-than-many-of-us|title=Robredo: Sister Fox 'more Filipino than many of us'|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On November 8, Robredo's team, which sought to aid the people of [[Boracay]], was barred from entering by government forces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/11/08/18/robredo-says-team-barred-from-boracay-during-closure|title=Robredo says team barred from Boracay during closure|last=News|first=Joyce Ann Clavecillas, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On November 17, Robredo lashed out at the 'special treatment' the government was providing for convicted criminal [[Imelda Marcos]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/11/17/18/robredo-sereno-binatikos-ang-special-treatment-kay-imelda-marcos|title=Robredo, Sereno binatikos ang 'special treatment' kay Imelda Marcos|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On November 21, Robredo called for transparency in government-sponsored deals with [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/11/21/18/vp-robredo-calls-for-transparency-in-ph-china-deals|title=VP Robredo calls for transparency in PH-China deals|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On November 26, Robredo called on the government to assure that troop deployments in [[Samar]], [[Negros Island|Negros]], and [[Bicol Region|Bicol]] would not lead to martial law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/11/26/18/robredo-govt-must-assure-troop-deployment-will-not-lead-to-martial-law|title=Robredo: Gov't must assure troop deployment will not lead to martial law|last=News|first=Adrian Ayalin, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, she hit out at the House for prioritizing the controversial federal charter that benefits political dynasties over economic bills that would benefit the poor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/12/05/18/robredo-hits-house-for-prioritizing-federal-charter-over-economic-bills|title=Robredo hits House for prioritizing federal charter over economic bills|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On December 10, Defense chief Lorenzana cleared Robredo of accusations of an alleged ouster plot against Duterte, stating that the accusations against Robredo were 'fake news again'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/12/11/18/fake-news-lorenzana-clears-robredo-in-alleged-duterte-ouster-plot|title='Fake news': Lorenzana clears Robredo in alleged Duterte ouster plot|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On December 21, Robredo condemned the assassination of Ako Bicol Partylist representative [[Rodel Batocabe]], a fellow Bicolano.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/12/22/18/batocabe-murder-must-not-be-the-new-normal-robredo-says|title=Batocabe murder \u2018must not be the new normal,\u2019 Robredo says|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On December 30, she led the [[Rizal Day]] rites after President Duterte did not attend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/multimedia/photo/12/31/18/robredo-leads-rizal-day-rites|title=Robredo leads Rizal Day rites|last=OVP/handout|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\n==== 2019 ====\nOn January 1, 2019, [[New Year's Day]], Robredo visited landslide-hit towns in [[Camarines Sur]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/02/19/robredo-visits-landslide-hit-camarines-sur-town|title=Robredo visits landslide-hit Camarines Sur town|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On January 15, 2019, she urged the Department of Foreign Affairs to take action amid the national data breach crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/happens/567|title=DFA data breach|website=philstar.com|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On January 26, she condemned the deadly Sulu blast at a Catholic cathedral in Jolo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/27/19/arroyo-robredo-condemn-deadly-sulu-blast|title=Arroyo, Robredo condemn deadly Sulu blast|last=News|first=Maria Cecilia Butardo, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the May 2019 elections, news circulated on multiple social media platforms, mainly on Facebook, claiming that Vice President Robredo would resign as Vice President should the opposition slate ''Otso Diretso'' lose the election; Robredo later debunked the news as fake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2019/05/16/148954/leni-robredo-debunks-post-saying-she-will-resign-if-otso-diretso-loses/|title=Leni Robredo debunks post saying she will 'resign' if Otso Diretso loses|last=Malasig|first=Jeline|date=2019-05-16|website=Interaksyon|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2019, the [[Philippine National Police|PNP]]\u2013[[Criminal Investigation and Detection Group]] (CIDG) filed charges against Robredo and other members of the [[Otso Diretso|opposition]] for \"sedition, cyber libel, libel, ''estafa'', harboring a criminal, and [[obstruction of justice]]\".<ref name=\"bikoy0719\">{{cite news |title=Robredo, ilang taga-oposisyon kinasuhan ng PNP-CIDG ukol sa 'Bikoy' videos |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/07/19/19/robredo-ilang-taga-oposisyon-kinasuhan-ng-pnp-cidg-ukol-sa-bikoy-videos |work=ABS-CBN News |language=Tagalog}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sedition raps: Solons, bishop hit \u2018stupid\u2019 PNP |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1143908/sedition-raps-solons-bishop-hit-stupid-pnp |accessdate=July 20, 2019 |work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2019, the PET released the results of the initial recount, widening her lead over Sen. Marcos by 15,093 votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/242823-robredo-widens-lead-over-marcos-results-pet-recount-pilot-provinces|title=Robredo widens lead over Marcos in recount in 3 pilot provinces|last=Tomacruz|first=Sofia|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/712238/robredo-lead-over-marcos-widened-after-recount-in-3-provinces/story/|title=Robredo lead over Marcos widened after recount in 3 provinces|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/10/18/19/caguiao-carpio-robredo-lead-grew-by-15000-votes-in-initial-poll-protest-recount|title=PET: Robredo lead grew by 15,000 votes in initial poll protest recount|last=News|first=Mike Navallo, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n\nOn October 23, 2019, Vice President Leni Robredo made a statement, saying that Duterte should allow the UN to investigate the war on drugs, and she added that a campaign has been \"a failure and a dent on the country's international image.\" Presidential spokesman [[Salvador Panelo]] slammed Robredo's remark, saying that her claim \"lacked factual basis.\" However, on October 27, 2019, Robredo clarified that she suggested for \"tweaks\" to the campaign and denied that she called to stop the war on drugs.\n\nOn November 4, 2019, Duterte assigned Robredo to be co-chairperson of the [[Inter-Agency Committee on Anti-Illegal Drugs]] (ICAD) until the end of his term in 2022, said presidential spokesman [[Salvador Panelo]]. <ref>[https://www.dpa-international.com/topic/duterte-appoints-vp-critic-war-drugs-lead-war-drugs-urn%3Anewsml%3Adpa.com%3A20090101%3A191105-99-586173]</ref>\n\n==== 2020 ====\nDuring the aftermath of the [[2020 Taal Volcano eruption]], she went to Batangas and Cavite, the most affected regions of the volcano eruption, on January 21st to distribute relief goods through her office and some partner organizations. The effort donated 1,500 food packs, 1,500 hygiene kits, and 1,500 sleeping mats for the victims. Leni herself also distributed [[Lugaw|lugaw]] (porridge) and [[Pandesal|pandesal]] to the victims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/249877-robredo-returns-batangas-cavite-give-more-aid-taal-volcano-eruption-evacuees|title=Robredo returns to Batangas, Cavite to give more aid to Taal evacuees|last=Cepeda|first=Mara|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn February 10, 2020, she was cleared of charges filed by the CIDG.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/725455/doj-clears-robredo-indicts-trillanes-and-10-others-for-conspiracy-to-commit-sedition/story/ | title=DOJ clears Robredo, indicts Trillanes and 10 others for 'conspiracy to commit sedition' | publisher=[[GMA News]] | date=February 10, 2020 | accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/251397-doj-resolution-conspiracy-commit-sedition-opposition | title=DOJ clears Robredo, charges Trillanes in sedition case | publisher=[[Rappler]] | date=February 10, 2020 | accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref> During the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|COVID-19 pandemic]], the Office of the Vice President provided free shuttle services for frontliners and emergency workers as the entire island of Luzon was put on an enhanced community quarantine. The office has also delivered 7,350 [[Personal protective equipment|personal protective equipment]] (PPEs) to nine hospitals, namely San Lazaro Hospital, the Philippine General Hospital, and UP-National Institutes of Health in Manila, and the Lung Center of the Philippines, Philippine Heart Center, Quirino Memorial Medical Center, Philippine Orthopedic Center, Veterans Memorial Medical Center, and East Avenue Medical Center in Quezon City. A total of \u20b117.3 million was raised for these donations, including food and care packages for the health workers and their families. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/robredo-donation-health-workers.html|title=Robredo donates gear to health workers, pledges free shuttle rides|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Issues ===\nNumerous [[fake news]] stories have been manufactured on [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]], [[YouTube]], and other blog sites against Robredo after she won the vice presidency in 2016. The instances of slander against her multiplied further after she expressed her dissent against the deadly [[Philippine Drug War]] of President [[Rodrigo Duterte]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/203309-leni-robredo-debunks-fake-news|title=Here's how Robredo debunks 'fake news' vs her|last=Cepeda|first=Mara|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> which has killed at least 20,000 Filipinos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/senator-rodrigo-duterte-drug-war-killed-20000-180221134139202.html|title=Senator: Rodrigo Duterte's drug war has killed 20,000|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> Robredo has demonstrated the falsehood of these statements against her. The majority of the fake news stories were fabricated by pro-Duterte bloggers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/breaking-news/2018/07/03/129890/rj-nieto-thinking-pinoy-free-speech-libel/|title=The libel charge against 'Thinking Pinoy' and the limits of free speech|last=Madarang|first=Catalina Ricci S.|date=2018-07-03|website=Interaksyon|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1019837/robredo-actions-of-mocha-uson-drew-olivar-do-not-help-duterte|title=Robredo: Actions of Mocha Uson, Drew Olivar do not help Duterte|last=Lalu|first=Gabriel Pabico|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> including those working under the Duterte government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//newsbreak/inside-track/201071-vice-president-leni-robredo-lies-bring-it-on|title=Robredo on lies: 'Bring it on'|last=Rappler.com|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nRobredo has been a constant victim of memes and \"fake news\" articles since taking office in 2016, some of which she claims emanate from a Senate source. Dealing with these, she said, was a \"test of character\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/05/12/vp-leni-intensify-efforts-to-punish-sources-of-fake-news|title=VP Leni: Intensify efforts to punish sources of fake news|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2017/12/24/vp-leni-in-2017-fake-news-snubs-impeachment-and-electoral-protest|title=VP Leni in 2017: Fake news, snubs, impeachment, and electoral protest|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2017/10/06/Robredo-hits-fake-news-sources.html|title=Robredo hits sources of fake news|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/994656/robredo-dealing-with-fake-news-public-criticism-a-test-of-character|title=Robredo: Dealing with fake news, public criticism a test of character|last=Ostria|first=Rey Anthony|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Leni Robredo's family July 2016.jpg|thumb|Robredo with her daughters.]]\nLeni was married to [[Jesse Robredo]], whom she met while working at the Bicol River Basin Development Program, from 1987 until his death from a [[2012 Philippine Piper Seneca crash|plane crash]] in 2012. The couple had three daughters: Jessica Marie \"Aika\" Robredo, Janine Patricia \"Tricia\" Robredo, and Jillian Therese Robredo.<ref name=\"Inquirer\"/><ref name=\"ABSCBNCOMwhirlwindromance\"/> Their eldest daughter, Aika,  was an executive assistant at the [[Office of Civil Defense (Philippines)|Office of Civil Defense]], while their second eldest, Tricia, is a medical student and was a [[UAAP]] basketball [[sideline reporter]] for [[National University (Philippines)|National University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=14 facts about the Philippines' 14th VP #10|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/image/nation/05/27/16/14-facts-about-the-philippines-14th-vp-10|accessdate=May 28, 2016|work=[[ABS-CBN News]]|date=May 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=de Vera|first1=Ruel|title=Aika Robredo\u2013Leni\u2019s secret campaign weapon|url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/227424/aika-robredo-lenis-secret-campaign-weapon|accessdate=May 28, 2016|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=April 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tricia Robredo's courtside reporting stint is for her dad|url=http://www.philstar.com/uaapseason76/articles/2013/08/16/1097911/tricia-robredos-courtside-reporting-stint-her-dad|accessdate=May 28, 2016|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=August 16, 2013}}</ref> Their youngest, Jilian, is currently studying biomolecular science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2018/08/23/1845174/robredos-daughter-study-new-york-university-full-scholarship|title=Robredo's daughter to study in New York University with full scholarship|website=philstar.com|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/994610/leni-robredo-graduation-harvard-ateneo-daughters-academic-rites|title=Proud mom VP Leni attends daughters\u2019 back-to-back academic rites|last=Esguerra|first=Anthony Q.|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nSince May 14, 2017, Robredo hosts her own public service radio program entitled ''BISErbisyong LENI'', aired on [[DZXL]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pasion|first1=Patty|title=Robredo to host own radio show starting May 14|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/169705-robredo-host-radio-show-may-14|accessdate=May 13, 2017|work=[[Rappler]]|date=May 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Honors and recognition ==\nRobredo was featured in an episode of ABS-CBN's drama anthology ''[[Maalaala Mo Kaya]]'' on February 6, 2016, three days before the official campaign period for national candidates in the 2016 elections. [[Dimples Romana]] played the role of Robredo, but [[Kaye Abad]] portrayed her in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections/2016/121192-leni-robredo-maalaala-mo-kaya-mmk|title=3 days before campaign, MMK to feature Robredo|work=[[Rappler]]|last=Cupin|first=Bea|date=February 3, 2016|accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2016, Robredo was awarded the Honorary Outstanding Woman Award of the Year 2016 by the [[Thailand|Thai]] government, coinciding with Thailand's Women's Day. The recognition was given to Robredo, citing her work and advocacy for [[women's empowerment]] and pushing for [[gender equality]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/141603-thailand-award-leni-robredo-women-empowerment|title=Robredo honored as 'outstanding woman' in Southeast Asia|last=Pasion|first=Patty|date=August 2, 2016|accessdate=August 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn August 23, 2016, Robredo was awarded the Most Influential Filipina Woman of the World award by Filipina Women's Network (FWN), a non-government organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2016/08/24/1616771/robredo-named-most-influential-filipina |title=Robredo named most influential Filipina |website=Philstar.com |date=August 24, 2016 |accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThree universities have conferred Robredo with honorary doctorates:\n\n* [[Polytechnic University of the Philippines]] (2015, Doctor in Public Administration),<ref name=\"Inquirer\" /> \n* [[University of Saint Anthony]] in [[Iriga]], [[Camarines Sur]], her home province (2017, Doctor of Humanities),<ref>{{cite news|last1=Patty|first1=Pasion|title=Look: Robredo receives honorary degree from Camarines Sur university|url=http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/inside-track/167390-robredo-honorary-degree-university-saint-anthony-camarines-sur|accessdate=April 21, 2017|work=[[Rappler]]|date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> \n* [[University of the Cordilleras]] (2017, Doctor of Laws).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Catajan|first1=Maria Elena|title=Robredo to youth: Be bearers of truth, empathy|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/161701|accessdate=February 20, 2019|publisher=[[SunStar]]|date=August 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title=Philippine vice presidential election, 2016<ref>https://ph.rappler.com/elections/2016/results/philippines/position/2/vice-president</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n|party=Liberal\n|candidate=Leni Robredo\n|votes=14,418,817\n|percentage=35.11%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=Independent politician\n|candidate=[[Bongbong Marcos]]\n|votes=14,155,344\n|percentage=34.47%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=Independent politician\n|candidate=[[Alan Peter Cayetano]]\t\n|votes=5,903,379\n|percentage=14.38%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=Independent politician\n|candidate=[[Francis Escudero]]\n|votes=4,931,962\n|percentage=12.01%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=Independent politician\n|candidate=[[Antonio Trillanes]]\n|votes=868,501\n|percentage=2.11%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=United Nationalist Alliance\n|candidate=[[Gregorio Honasan]]\n|votes=788,881\n|percentage=1.92%\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n|votes=41,066,884\n|percentage=100.00%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons}}\n* {{Official website|https://lenirobredo.com/}}\n* [http://www.congress.gov.ph/members/search.php?id=robredo-m Profile] at the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160703170051/http://www.bayangmatuwid.org/lp/candidate/Leni_Robredo/ Profile] at ''Bayang Matuwid''\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Offices and distinctions\n|list1=\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ph-lwr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Luis Villafuerte]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]] from [[Camarines Sur]]'s [[Legislative districts of Camarines Sur#3rd District|3rd District]]|years=2013\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=Gabriel Bordado}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jejomar Binay]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairwoman of [[Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council (Philippines)|Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council]]|years=2016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Leoncio Evasco Jr.]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jejomar Binay]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Vice President of the Philippines]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-new|position}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Co-Chairperson on the [[Inter-Agency Committee on Anti-Illegal Drugs]]|years=2019\u2013present|alongside=[[Aaron Aquino]]}}\n{{s-inc}}\n\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Benigno Aquino III]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairwoman of [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n\n{{s-prec}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rodrigo Duterte]]|as=[[President of the Philippines|President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Philippine order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the Philippines]]<br />{{small|''as [[Vice President of the Philippines|Vice President]]''}}}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Benigno Aquino III]]|as=Former [[President of the Philippines|President]]}}\n\n{{S-other|line}}\n{{s-new|first}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Philippine presidential line of succession]]<br />{{small|''as [[Vice President of the Philippines|Vice President]]''}}}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Vicente Sotto III]]|as=[[President of the Senate of the Philippines]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n}}\n\n{{Leni Robredo}}\n{{Philippine Vice Presidents}}\n{{Duterte Cabinet}}\n{{Candidates in the Philippine presidential election, 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robredo, Leni}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Vice Presidents of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Bicolano politicians]]\n[[Category:Filipino women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (Philippines) politicians]]\n[[Category:Vice-presidential candidates in the 2016 Philippine presidential election]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Representatives of the Philippines from Camarines Sur]]\n[[Category:People from Naga, Camarines Sur]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines Diliman alumni]]\n[[Category:San Beda University alumni]]\n[[Category:Chairpersons of the Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Duterte Administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:Filipino radio personalities]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the House of Representatives of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Cabinet of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Women vice presidents]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Philippine name|Santo Tomas|Gerona|Robredo|ph=widowed}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[Excellency|Her Excellency]]\n| name = Leni Robredo\n| image = VP Leni Meeting with Pres Duterte Cropped 2016.jpg\n| office1 = [[List of Vice Presidents of the Philippines|14th]] [[Vice President of the Philippines]]\n| president1 = [[Rodrigo Duterte]]\n| term_start1 = June 30, 2016\n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Jejomar Binay]]\n| successor1 = \n| office2 = Co-Chairperson of the [[Inter-Agency Committee on Anti-Illegal Drugs]]\n| alongside2   = Aaron Aquino\n| president2 = [[Rodrigo Duterte]]\n| term_start2 = November 6, 2019\n| term_end2 = November 24, 2019\n| office3 = Chair of the [[Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council (Philippines)|Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council]]\n| term_start3 = July 12, 2016\n| term_end3 = December 5, 2016\n| president3 = Rodrigo Duterte\n| predecessor3 = [[Jejomar Binay]]\n| successor3 = [[Leoncio Evasco Jr.]]\n| office4 = Member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]]<br />from [[Camarines Sur]]'s [[Legislative districts of Camarines Sur#3rd District|3rd District]]\n| term_start4 = June 30, 2013\n| term_end4 = June 30, 2016\n| predecessor4 = [[Luis Villafuerte]]\n| successor4 = [[Gabriel Bordado]]\n| birth_name = Maria Leonor Santo Tomas Gerona\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1965|4|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Naga, Camarines Sur|Naga]], [[Camarines Sur]], Philippines\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Jesse Robredo]]|1987|August 18, 2012|end=died}}\n| children = 3\n| residence = [[Quezon City Reception House]]\n| education = [[University of the Philippines Diliman]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}}<br />[[San Beda University]] {{small|([[Master of Laws|LL.M.]])}}<br />[[University of Nueva Caceres]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]])}}\n| website = {{url|lenirobredo.com|Official website}}<br />{{url|ovp.gov.ph|Government website}}\n| honorific_prefix = [[Excellency|Her Excellency]]\n}}\n{{Leni Robredo sidebar}}\n'''Maria Leonor''' \"'''Leni'''\" '''Gerona Robredo''' (born '''Maria Leonor Santo Tomas Gerona'''; April 23, 1965)<ref name=\"bandera1\">{{cite web |url=http://bandera.inquirer.net/121461/leni-im-tough-i-fight-for-what-is-right |title=Leni: I\u2019m tough, I fight for what is right |author=Leifbilly Begas |publisher=Bandera |date=May 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Inquirer\">{{cite news|title=Vote PH 2016: Leni Robredo|url=http://www.inquirer.net/elections2016/leni-robredo|accessdate=April 12, 2016|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=April 10, 2016}}</ref> is a [[Filipino people|Filipina]] lawyer and social activist who is the [[List of Vice Presidents of the Philippines|14th and incumbent]] [[Vice President of the Philippines]]. Running under the [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]], Robredo won the vice-presidency contest in the [[2016 Philippine presidential election|May 9, 2016 election]], as confirmed and proclaimed by the [[Congressional canvass for the Philippine presidential election, 2016|official Congressional count of May 25\u201327]],<ref name=\"Philstar 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2016/05/27/1587569/duterte-robredo-win-final-official-tally|title=Official count: Duterte is new president, Robredo is vice president|date=May 27, 2016|work=CNN Philippines|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> with 14,418,817 votes (35.11% of the votes), narrowly defeating Senator [[Bongbong Marcos]] by 263,473 votes.<ref name=\"Inquirer 1\">{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/787873/leni-robredo-is-vice-president|title=Leni Robredo is vice president|last=Cayabyab|first=Marc Jayson|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|access-date=May 27, 2016}}</ref> A report released by the Presidential Electoral Tribunal further widened her lead to 278,566 over Senator Marcos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=36cce290-f260-11e9-aefe-116bb3791ffc&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxOS0xMC0xOS9waGlsaXBwaW5lLXZwLXJvYnJlZG8td2lkZW5zLWxlYWQtb3Zlci1tYXJjb3MtaW4tcHJvdGVzdC1yZWNvdW50|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref> She is the second woman to serve as Vice President after [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]] and the first Vice President from [[Bicol Region|Bicol]].\n\nRobredo first came to public attention in 2012 after the death of her husband, [[Secretary of the Interior and Local Government (Philippines)|Interior Secretary]] [[Jesse Robredo]], in the [[2012 Philippine Piper Seneca crash]] off the coast of [[Masbate Island]]. Prior to the accident, her involvement in public life was as a lawyer and social activist. After this, she ran in the [[2013 Philippine general election|2013 general election]] and won as the representative of [[Camarines Sur]]'s [[Legislative district of Naga|Third District]] to the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]] for the [[16th Congress of the Philippines|16th Congress]], a post she held until her inauguration as Vice President on June 30, 2016.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMaria Leonor Santo Tomas Gerona was born on April 23, 1965 in [[Naga, Camarines Sur]], Philippines.<ref name=\"RAPPLERrunning\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections/2016/108123-leni-robredo-vice-presidential-bet|title=Leni Robredo: I can't refuse call to serve|work=Rappler}}</ref>  She was the first of three children born to retired Naga City Regional Trial Court Judge Antonio Gerona and Salvacion Santo Tomas.<ref name=\"INQknew\">[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/256594/that-first-night-i-knew-he-was-gone-robredos-wife That first night, I knew he was gone\u2014Robredo\u2019s wife] Inquirer.net (retrieved June 13, 2014)</ref>\n\nLeni Gerona attended the basic education department of [[Universidad de Sta. Isabel]] in Naga, graduating from elementary school in 1978, and from high school in 1982. She then graduated with a degree in economics from the [[University of the Philippines School of Economics|UP School of Economics]] at the [[University of the Philippines Diliman]], in 1986. She then went to study law at [[University of Nueva Caceres]], graduating in 1992.<ref name=\"Inquirer\"/> After studying law, she took up her [[master's degree]] at [[San Beda University]] (then San Beda College).\n\n== Early career ==\nInspired by the [[People Power Revolution]] after graduating from UP Diliman,<ref name=\"RAPPLERprofile2016\">{{Citation |last = Francisco |first = Katerina |title = Leni Robredo: Low-key political wife goes national |journal = Rappler.com |volume = |issue = |pages = |date = October 5, 2015 |access-date = April 15, 2016 |url =http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections/2016/108017-leni-robredo-profile-2016}}</ref> Gerona chose to temporarily forego law studies and instead decided to work as a researcher for the Bicol River Basin Development Program (BRBDP),<ref name=\"ROGUEapril2016\"/> a government agency tasked with integrated area development planning in the three provinces of the [[Bicol Region|Bicol region]].<ref name=\"ABSCBNCOMwhirlwindromance\">http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/10/09/15/leni-robredo-relives-whirlwind-romance-jesse Leni Robredo relives 'whirlwind' romance with Jesse</ref> Here she met then-Program Director [[Jesse Robredo]], who would eventually become her husband.<ref name=\"ABSCBNCOMwhirlwindromance\"/>\n\nHaving passed the bar on her second attempt in 1996,<ref name=\"Inquirer\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/777063/bar-flunker-leni-robredo-tells-of-rebound| title = Bar flunker Leni Robredo tells of rebound| work = Philippine Daily Inquirer | accessdate = February 24, 2017| date = March 31, 2016| last = Yap |first = DJ}}</ref> Robredo served in the [[Public Attorney's Office (Philippines)|Public Attorney's Office]],<ref name=\"RAPPLERprofile2016\"/> a role in which she often took up the defense for cases pursued by her husband, who by then had become Mayor of Naga.<ref name=\"ROGUEapril2016\"/>\n\nFrom 1998 to 2008, Robredo became the coordinator of [[Sentro ng Alternatibong Lingap Panligan]] (SALIGAN), a Naga-based alternative legal support group.<ref name=\"ROGUEapril2016\">{{cite journal |last = Melendez |first = Paolo Enrico |title = The Evolution of Leni Robredo: How the VP Underdog Became the Race\u2019s Strongest Contender |journal = Rogue Magazine |volume = |issue = |pages = |publisher = Rogue Media, Inc. |location = Makati |date = April 22, 2016 |url = http://rogue.ph/the-evolution-of-leni-robredo-how-the-vp-underdog-became-the-races-strongest-contender/ |accessdate = April 23, 2016 }}</ref> SALIGAN's work<ref name=\"ROGUEapril2016\"/> \naimed to encourage young legal professionals to take on leadership roles,<ref>{{cite web|title = Will children make good leaders? {{!}} Mindanao Times|url = http://mindanaotimes.net/will-children-make-good-leaders/|website = mindanaotimes.net|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> and involved visiting distant rural communities to provide legal services to residents who would otherwise have little or no access to such services,<ref name=\"SALIGANpep\">{{cite AV media |people = |title =How Leni Robredo and her group help empower women and farmers |medium = YouTube Video |publisher =  Philippine Entertainment Portal, Inc. |location = Mandaluyong City |date = April 12, 2016 |url = http://www.pep.ph/electionwatch2016/media/13931/pep-talk-election-watch-how-leni-robredo-and-her-group-help-empower-women-and-farmers#MF53myyl05pEU2Du.99}}</ref> as well as conducting legal advocacy by proposing amendments and new laws based on the needs of these marginalized communities.  Later, the group's focus shifted to include helping rural women to acquire capital in order to participate in competitive markets.<ref name=\"SALIGANpep\"/>\n\nIn addition, Robredo founded the Lakas ng Kababaihan ng Naga Federation, an organization that provides training and livelihood opportunities for women, in 1989.<ref name=\"RAPPLERwomensadvocacy\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections/2016/108171-leni-robredo-bicol-women-group-support |title=No fears that Robredo will neglect CamSur \u2013 women supporters |work=Rappler.com |date=October 5, 2015 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Robredo was named the chairperson of the Liberal Party in Camarines Sur.<ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/275614/robredo-widow-now-liberal-party-head-in-camsur Robredo widow now Liberal Party head in CamSur] Inquirer.net (October 5, 2012)</ref><ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/283510/leni-robredo-files-candidacy-for-house-seat Leni Robredo files candidacy for House seat] Inquirer.net (October 5, 2012)</ref><ref>[http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/regions/10/05/12/leni-robredo-ready-enter-politics Leni Robredo ready to enter politics] ABS-CBNnews.com (October 5, 2012)</ref><ref>[http://www.rappler.com/nation/12919-leni-robredo-appointed-lp-chair-in-camsur Leni Robredo appointed LP chair in CamSur] Rappler.com (October 5, 2012)</ref><ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/279062/leni-robredo-eyes-rtc-judge-post-in-qc Leni Robredo eyes RTC judge post in QC] Inquirer.net (October 5, 2012)</ref>\n\n== Congressional career ==\n[[File:Unveiling Robredo monument at Cararayan National HS.jpg|thumb|left|Leni Robredo unveiling the Jesse Robredo Monument at the Cararayan National High School in Naga, May 27, 2016]]\n\nRobredo ran in [[Camarines Sur]]'s 3rd congressional district during the [[2013 Philippine general election|Philippine general elections of 2013]]. On May 16, 2013 she was proclaimed winner, beating Nelly Favis-Villafuerte (of [[Nationalist People's Coalition]]/[[United Nationalist Alliance]]), wife of former Congressman [[Luis Villafuerte]]<ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/410263/leni-robredo-proclaimed-winner-in-camarines-sur Leni Robredo proclaimed winner in Camarines Sur], Philippine Daily Inquirer</ref> and member of the politically powerful Villafuerte dynasty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/785167/political-dynasties-win-some-lose-some |title=Political dynasties win some, lose some &#124; Inquirer News |publisher=Newsinfo.inquirer.net |date= |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Leni Robredo in a Quezon City LP campaign rally.jpg|left|thumb|Robredo delivering a speech during a LP campaign rally in Quezon City, February 17, 2016]]\nDuring her term in congress, Robredo was the vice chairman of the House committees on good governance, public accountability, and revision of laws, and a member of 11 other house panels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/539542/news/nation/leni-robredo-the-reluctant-candidate-now-seeks-vp-post-in-2016|title=Leni Robredo: The reluctant candidate now seeks VP post in 2016|work=GMA News Online}}</ref> She was known for being a strong advocate of the [[Freedom of Information Act]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/654464/leni-robredo-urges-adoption-of-house-foi-bill-version|title=Leni Robredo urges adoption of House FOI bill version|author=Marc Jayson Cayabyab|publisher=}}</ref> and a strong supporter of the [[Bangsamoro Basic Law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/692588/list-how-did-your-representatives-vote-on-the-bbl|title=LIST: How did your representatives vote on the BBL?|author=Aries Joseph Hegina|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cagayan-de-oro/local-news/2015/05/12/22-house-members-urge-support-bbl-407119|title=22 House members urge support for Bangsamoro Basic Law|work=Sun.Star}}</ref>\n\nParticipatory governance and transparency were major thrusts of Robredo's legislative agenda. The first law Robredo authored in congress was the Full Disclosure Policy Bill (HB 19), which would have mandated all government agencies and their sub-units and projects to disclose their budget and financial transactions in a conspicuous manner \"without any requests from the public.\"<ref>{{cite web|title = Leni Robredo's first bill: Full disclosure in gov't transactions|url = http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2013/07/01/960401/leni-robredos-first-bill-full-disclosure-govt-transactions|website = philstar.com|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref>  Concerned that the marginalized sector should not be denied access to government frontline services and public meetings based on their attire,<ref>{{cite web|title = Leni Robredo eyes lifting of gov\u2019t dress code for ordinary Filipinos - Liberal Party of the Philippines|url = http://www.liberalparty.org.ph/leni-robredo-eyes-lifting-of-govt-dress-code-for-ordinary-filipinos/|website = Liberal Party of the Philippines|accessdate = December 3, 2015|language = en-US}}</ref> she sponsored the Open Door Policy Act (House Bill No. 6286),<ref name=\"HB6286\">{{cite web|title = House Bill No. 6286 (Open Door Policy Act).pdf|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5id4DkjPBsDS2ZaaTRXblVuR2M/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> which prohibits government offices and agencies from implementing strict dress codes.<ref name=\"HB6286\"/>\n\nRobredo also authored the People Empowerment Bill (HB 4911<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|title = Leni on BUB, cabinet portfolio and others - Liberal Party of the Philippines|url = http://www.liberalparty.org.ph/leni-on-bub-cabinet-portfolio-and-others/|website = Liberal Party of the Philippines|accessdate = December 3, 2015|language = en-US}}</ref>), which sought to allow more participation from Filipinos in decision and policy-making,<ref>{{cite web|title = [HB4911] People Empowerment Bill.pdf|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BwpCSR3_0B62cXJ0UTBJeHJQYzQ/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> and the Participatory Budget Process Bill (HB 3905), which sought to increase participation in budget-related decisions in government projects by locals.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite AV media | people = [[Maria Ressa]] (Interviewer), Leni Robredo | title = Rappler Talk: Leni Robredo on running for VP  | medium = YouTube Video | publisher = [[Rappler]] | location = | date = October 12, 2015 | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kqyTy1HZcu8 | accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref>  She also wrote the Comprehensive Anti-Discrimination Bill (HB 3432) to prohibit discrimination on the basis of ethnicity, race, religion or belief, sex, gender, sexual orientation, gender identity and expressions, language, disability, HIV status, etc.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nTo promote transparency in the taxation process, she sponsored the house version (House Bill 05831) of what would eventually become Republic Act RA10708, the Tax Incentives Management and Transparency Act of 2009 (TIMTA).<ref>{{cite web|title = Senate passes Tax Incentives Management and Transparency Act|url = http://www.rappler.com/business/economy-watch/95691-senate-passes-tax-incentives-management-transparency-act|website = Rappler|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2015/06/14/1465668/house-oks-tax-incentives-transparency-bill|title=House OKs Tax Incentives Transparency bill|work=philstar.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bworldonline.com/content.php?section=Opinion&title=grief-and-why-i-will-campaign-for-leni&id=119434|title=BusinessWorld - Grief, and why I will campaign for Leni|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nConcerned about corruption in [[agrarian reform]], Robredo co-authored House Bill 5841, which would have created an Agrarian Reform Commission that will focus on investigating violations against the [[Comprehensive Agrarian Reform Program]] (CARP).<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref>{{cite web|title = Leni Robredo: Probe corruption in land distribution - Liberal Party of the Philippines|url = http://www.liberalparty.org.ph/leni-robredo-probe-corruption-in-land-distribution/|website = Liberal Party of the Philippines|accessdate = December 3, 2015|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\nOther major legislation co-authored by Robredo includes the Anti-Dynasty Bill<ref>{{cite web|title = Cong. Robredo's Statement on the Anti-Dynasty Bill - Leni Robredo Official Website|url = http://www.lenirobredo.com/cong-robredos-statement-on-the-passage-of-the-anti-dynasty-bill/|website = Leni Robredo Official Website|accessdate = December 3, 2015|language = en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Robredo: Dynasty bill may be passed yet|url = http://www.philstar.com/region/2015/09/05/1496249/robredo-dynasty-bill-may-be-passed-yet|website = philstar.com|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> and the Healthy Beverage Options Act (House Bill 4021).<ref>{{cite web|title = Healthy Beverage Options Act 4021 Proposed for Schools|url = http://www.smartparenting.com.ph/news/healthy-beverage-options-act-4021-proposed-for-schools|website = SmartParenting.com.ph|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Legislative portfolio ===\nAs a member of the 16th Congress, Robredo was one of the principal authors of the house version of \u201cThe Tax Incentives Management and Transparency Act (TIMTA)\u201d (Republic Act RA10708, House Bill 05831), which was enacted on December 9, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/members/search.php?id=robredo-m&pg=auth |title=House of Representatives |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |date= |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> She also co-authored the house version<ref name=\"CongressCoAuth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/members/search.php?id=robredo-m&pg=coauth |title=House of Representatives |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |date= |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> of the following laws: the \u201cNational Children\u2019s Month Act,\u201d Republic Act RA10661 (HB01641) enacted on May 29, 2015, declaring the celebration of the national children's month on November of every year;<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ronda|first1=Rainier Allan|title=November declared National Children\u2019s Month|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2015/06/07/1463080/november-declared-national-childrens-month|accessdate=July 9, 2016|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=June 7, 2015}}</ref> the \u201cCharter of the Quezon City Development Authority,\u201d Republic Act RA10646 (HB03899), lapsed into law on November 8, 2014; the \u201cOpen High School System Act,\u201d Republic Act RA10665 (HB04085) enacted on July 9, 2015, establishing and appropriating funds for the open [[Education in the Philippines#Secondary education|high school system]]; Republic Act RA10638 (HB04089), extending the corporate life of the [[Philippine National Railways]] for another 50 years, enacted on June 16, 2014; Republic Act RA10707 (HB04147), amending the \u201cProbation Law of 1976\u201d enacted on November 26, 2015, rationalizing and strengthening the [[probation]] system; the \u201cGraphic Health Warnings Law,\u201d Republic Act RA10643 (HB04590), enacted on November 15, 2014, prescribing the printing of graphic health warnings on [[tobacco]] products; Republic Act RA10655 (HB05280), decriminalizing [[Remarriage|premature remarriages]], enacted on March 13, 2015; and the \u201cSangguniang Kabataan Reform Act.of 2015,\u201d Republic Act RA10742 (HB06043), enacted on January 15, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title =Republic Act RA10655|url=http://www.gov.ph/downloads/2015/03mar/20150313-RA-10655-BSA.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Article 351 of Act No. 3815 of the revised penal code|url=http://www.ilo.org/dyn/natlex/docs/ELECTRONIC/57377/102476/F1830355101/PHL57377.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Noy signs law decriminalizing women\u2019s \u2018premature marriage\u2019 |url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2015/03/29/1438678/noy-signs-law-decriminalizing-womens-premature-marriage}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Robredo was one of many co-authors of the National Budgets for the years 2014 (RA10633, HB02630, enacted on December 20, 2013), 2015 (RA10651, HB04968, enacted on December 23, 2014), and 2016 (RA10717, HB06132, enacted on December 22, 2015).<ref name=\"CongressCoAuth\"/>\n\nRobredo was also a key supporter of: HB 4911: People Empowerment Bill to create a partnership between local governments and civil society through the establishment of a people's council in every local government unit. This act also prescribes the powers and functions of said council;<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title = [HB03432] Comprehesive Anti-Discrimination.pdf|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BwpCSR3_0B62WHllSlNyT2xFbVE/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> HB 3432: Comprehensive Anti-Discrimination to prohibit discrimination on the basis of ethnicity, race, religion or belief, sex, gender, sexual orientation, gender identity and expressions, language, disability, HIV status, and other status, and provide penalties for these;<ref name=\"auto\"/> HB 4021: Healthy Beverage Options to regulate the availability of beverages to children in schools and for other purposes;<ref>{{cite web|title = [HB4021] Healthy Beverage Options Bill.PDF|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BwpCSR3_0B62M1RhQ1l4YXg4ZG8/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> HB 19: Full Disclosure Policy to require the full disclosure of all information on fiscal management from all national government departments, bureaus, agencies, and other instrumentalities, including government-owned or controlled corporations and their subsidiaries and local governments. This act will also provide penalties for violations of said requirements;<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|title = [HB3237] Freedom of Information.pdf|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BwpCSR3_0B62ZHk4dHd5T1NiVTg/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> HB 3905: Participatory Budget Process to institutionalize citizens\u2019 participation in the budget process and for other processes;<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|title = [HB03905] BUB.pdf|url = https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BwpCSR3_0B62ZTZLMW1rbFBLSzQ/view|website = Google Docs|accessdate = December 3, 2015}}</ref> and HB 3237: Freedom of Information to strengthen the right of citizens to information held by the government.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n== Vice presidency ==\n{{Infobox President styles\n|name= Leni Robredo\n|image = [[File:Seal of the Vice President of the Republic of the Philippines.svg|50px]]\n|dipstyle= [[Excellency|Her Excellency]]\n|offstyle= Your Excellency\n|altstyle= Madame Vice President\n}}\n=== Timeline ===\nOn October 5, 2015, after her three daughters set aside their initial objections, Robredo announced that she would run for the post of [[Vice President of the Philippines]] under the [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]] in the [[2016 Philippine presidential election|2016 election]], as the running mate of presidential candidate [[Mar Roxas]].<ref name=\"RAPPLERrunning\"/> Robredo won the election with 14,418,817 votes, or 35.11 percent of cast ballots, narrowly defeating her closest rival, Senator [[Bongbong Marcos]], by 263,473 votes or by 0.64 percent.<ref name=\"Inquirer 1\"/>\n\nRobredo was sworn in as Vice President of the Philippines on June 30, 2016 at the [[Quezon City Reception House]], which she had since used as her office.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2016/06/30/LOOK-Leni-Robredo-takes-oath-of-office-as-Vice-President-of-the-Philippines.html|title=LOOK: Leni Robredo takes oath of office as Vice President of the Philippines|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|date=June 30, 2016|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== 2016 ====\nRobredo first met President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] personally at the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] change-of-command ceremonies at [[Camp Aguinaldo]] on July 1, 2016, a day after their inauguration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/07/01/16/cordial-at-first-sight-duterte-robredo-meet|title=Cordial at first sight: Duterte, Robredo meet|work=[[ABS-CBN News]]|last=Alberto-Masakayan|first=Thea|date=July 1, 2016|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> She later paid a [[courtesy call]] on him at [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace]] on July 4, their first formal meeting.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alvarez|first1=Kathrina Charmaine|last2=Dioquino|first2=Rose-An Jessica|title=Robredo pays courtesy call on Duterte in Malaca\u00f1ang|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/572332/news/nation/robredo-pays-courtesy-call-on-duterte-in-malacanang|accessdate=July 8, 2016|work=[[GMA News]]|date=July 4, 2016}}</ref> On July 7, Duterte called Robredo during a press conference to offer her the cabinet position of head of the [[Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council (Philippines)|Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council]], which Robredo accepted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/794898/duterte-appoints-robredo-as-hudcc-chief|title=Duterte appoints Robredo as HUDCC chief and Vice President Leni Robredo was eventually fired from the Duterte Cabinet and did not quit out of her own accord.  |newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRobredo is the third Vice President to head the government agency focused on housing programs, following her immediate predecessors [[Noli de Castro]] and [[Jejomar Binay]]. Duterte earlier said that he did not want to appoint a cabinet position to Robredo due to his unfamiliarity with her and his friendship with Bongbong Marcos.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ranada|first1=Pia|title=VP Robredo is Duterte's housing czar|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/138974-duterte-offers-robredo-cabinet-post|accessdate=July 7, 2016|work=[[Rappler]]|date=July 7, 2016}}</ref> On August 2, the government of [[Thailand]] bestowed upon Robredo the 'Honorary Outstanding Women Award' of Southeast Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/141603-thailand-award-leni-robredo-women-empowerment|title=Robredo honored as 'outstanding woman' in Southeast Asia|last=Pasion|first=Patty|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 23, non-governmental organization Filipina Women's Network bestowed on Robredo the 'Most Influential Filipina Woman of the World Award'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spot.ph/newsfeatures/the-latest-news-features/67528/robredo-most-influential-filipina-woman-of-the-world-a00171-20160824|title=NGO names VP Robredo as \"Most Influential Filipina\"|date=August 24, 2016|website=SPOT.PH|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, after the onslaught of [[Typhoon Meranti (2016)|Typhoon Ferdie]] in Batanes, Robredo visited the island and brought emergency shelter assistance to the people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/816574/leni-visits-typhoon-damaged-batanes|title=Leni visits typhoon-damaged Batanes|first=Juliet|last=Catalu\u00f1a|work=inquirer.net|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref>  In the same month, Robredo met with [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines]] (CBCP) president Lingayen-Dagupan Archbishop [[Socrates B. Villegas]] to discuss drug rehabilitation programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/146826-robredo-cbcp-villegas-drug-rehabilitation-programs|title=Robredo meets CBCP's Villegas on drug rehab|work=rappler.com|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, international aid agencies threw their full support behind the antipoverty program of Vice President Leni Robredo, joining a summit scheduled for the same month, where they partnered with the country's poorest local government units. The summit, known as Partnerships Against Poverty Summit, held on October 10, is a product of Robredo's twice-weekly visits to the poorest local government units (LGUs) in her first 100 days as Vice President. Some of the participants of the summit, such as the UN Children's Fund, World Food Program, the UN Development Program, the EU, the World Bank, and the Asian Development Bank, promised to help in \u201cresearch, knowledge sharing, technical assistance, small grants for capacity building and the like,\u201d according to Georgina Hernandez, head of the OVP's Anti-Poverty and Advocacies Programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/822207/intl-aid-agencies-back-robredos-antipoverty-program|title=Int\u2019l aid agencies back Robredo\u2019s antipoverty program|first=Nikko|last=Dizon|work=inquirer.net|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref> Following the effects of [[Typhoon Haima (2016)|Super Typhoon Lawin]], Robredo visited Cagayan and met with Cagayan Governor Manuel Mamba and local disaster officials to inquire about the damage, in order to ascertain the kind of assistance her office could provide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/news/10/21/16/robredo-visits-typhoon-ravaged-cagayan|title=Robredo visits typhoon-ravaged Cagayan|first=Harris Julio, ABS-CBN|last=News|work=abs-cbn.com|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref>  Robredo's anti-poverty program, also known ''Angat Buhay Program'', has benefited 83,707 families across the country in its first year of implementation.<ref name=\"rappler.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/184678-senate-ovp-2018-budget-angat-buhay-leni-robredo|title=Senate adds P20M to Robredo's budget for her anti-poverty program|last=Elemia|first=Camille|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On November 17, Robredo was bestowed the TOWN's Tanglaw Award for 'championing women's rights' and 'empowering the marginalized'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/152758-leni-robredo-towns-tanglaw-award|title=Robredo receives TOWNS special award|last=Pasion|first=Patty|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn December 4, 2016, Robredo was informed by Cabinet Secretary [[Leoncio Evasco Jr.]] \"to desist from attending all Cabinet meetings starting December 5\", which prompted her to release a statement tendering her resignation as the chairwoman of the Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council, effective the following day.<ref>{{cite news|title=VP Leni Robredo resigns from Cabinet position|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2016/12/04/vp-leni-robredo-resigns-cabinet.html|accessdate=December 4, 2016|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|date=December 4, 2016}}</ref>  Duterte supporters have tried to impeach her as Vice President for criticizing his bloody anti-drug crackdown and other policies.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/duterte-wants-impeachment-bids-against-philippine-vp-stopped/2017/03/23/00dd5d5e-0fb9-11e7-aa57-2ca1b05c41b8_story.html</ref>\n\n==== 2017 ====\nDuring the [[Marawi crisis]], Robredo called for unity as government troops engaged in a firefight against the [[Maute group]] in [[Marawi]], and she organized donations and directed relief operations for the victims.<ref name=\"robredocallsdonations\">{{cite news|last1=Adel|first1=Rosette|title=Robredo calls for donation for Marawi attack victims|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2017/05/24/1703144/robredo-calls-donation-marawi-attack-victims|newspaper=Philippine Star|date=May 24, 2017|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"groupscalldonations\">{{cite news|title=Groups call for donations for crisis-hit Marawi|url=http://www.rappler.com/move-ph/170756-groups-call-donations-relief-operations-marawi|work=[[Rappler]]|date=May 24, 2017|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"robredoreliefoperations\">{{cite news|title=Robredo orders relief operations amid Marawi clashes|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/170757-robredo-lawmakers-marawi-clashes-mindanao-martial-law|work=[[Rappler]]|date=May 24, 2017|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref>  She then visited wounded soldiers in [[Iligan]] to give support and contributions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robredo visits wounded soldiers in Iligan|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/news/05/29/17/robredo-visits-wounded-soldiers-in-iligan|accessdate=June 1, 2017|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs]]|date=May 29, 2017}}</ref> Robredo respects President Duterte's [[Proclamation No. 216|implementation]] of [[Martial law in the Philippines|martial law]] in the whole of Mindanao as a way to combat [[Terrorism in the Philippines|terrorism]], but has requested measures to ensure that the implementation would not resemble the \"abuses and violations\" during [[Ferdinand Marcos]]' implementation of [[Proclamation No. 1081]]. She also questioned the coverage and prolongation of the implementation and called on members of the Congress to review and validate the implementation as a \"constitutional duty\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Antonio|first1=Raymund|title=Leni backs Digong\u2019s drive against terrorism|url=http://news.mb.com.ph/2017/05/28/leni-backs-digongs-drive-against-terrorism/|accessdate=June 1, 2017|work=[[Manila Bulletin]]|date=May 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPresident Rodrigo Duterte skipped participation in what would have been his first Independence Day rites due to exhaustion.  Vice President Robredo, as the second highest-ranking official of the country, led the flag-raising and wreath-laying ceremonies during the 119th anniversary of Philippine independence. Foreign Affairs Secretary Alan Peter Cayetano stood beside her as Duterte's representative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/904816/full-text-vice-president-leni-robredo-independence-day-speech|title=FULL TEXT: Vice President Leni Robredo Independence Day speech|last=INQUIRER.net|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On July 6, the Philippine Quill Award was awarded to Lifestyle Asia for the Leni Robredo Cover Story of \u201cRise of a Stateswoman\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lifestyleasia.onemega.com/philippine-quill-awards-leni-robredo/|title=Lifestyle Asia wins a Philippine Quill Award for Leni Robredo Cover Story \"Rise of a Stateswoman\"|last=Ang|first=Sam|date=2017-07-06|website=Lifestyle Asia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, the Senate increased the 2018 budget of the Office of the Vice President (OVP) by \u20b120 million, which was allotted for the Vice President's Angat Buhay program.<ref name=\"rappler.com\"/>  In the same month, Robredo called on fellow Filipinos to remember the 165 soldiers and police who gave their lives for the liberation of Marawi City. Robredo said her office was already preparing to help in the rehabilitation of Marawi City, primarily through its flagship anti-poverty program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/186735-robredo-filipinos-remember-marawi-heroes-undas|title=Robredo urges Filipinos to remember Marawi heroes during Undas|last=Rappler.com|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\n==== 2018 ====\nOn May 6, 2018, Robredo slammed [[China]] for establishing [[missile]]s in the west [[Philippine Sea]]. The missiles were aimed directly at the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/05/06/18/robredo-slams-beijing-missiles-in-west-ph-sea|title=Robredo slams Beijing 'missiles' in West PH Sea|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On June 19, Robredo condemned the formal ouster of Chief Justice [[Maria Lourdes Sereno]], whom Duterte declared as his 'enemy'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/06/19/18/fight-for-democracy-robredo-says-after-sc-upholds-sereno-ouster|title='Fight for democracy,' Robredo says after SC upholds Sereno ouster|last=News|first=Adrian Ayalin, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Robredo formally accepted the role as leader of the opposition, unifying numerous parties in the House of Representatives and in the Senate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/07/10/18/robredo-led-united-opposition-to-release-senatorial-slate-in-september|title=Robredo-led 'united opposition' to release senatorial slate in September|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On July 10, President Duterte called Robredo 'incompetent' because she was a 'woman', sparking a feminist backlash against Duterte.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/07/10/18/duterte-calls-robredo-incompetent|title=Duterte calls Robredo 'incompetent'|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On the same day, Robredo revealed that defeated candidate Marcos 'lied' about the PET-revisor outing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/07/10/18/robredo-marcos-lying-about-pet-revisor-outing|title=Robredo: Marcos 'lying' about PET-revisor outing|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On July 26, the PET sided with Robredo and held a ballot shading threshold of the vice presidential electoral protest at 25 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/07/26/18/comelec-sides-with-robredo-holds-ballot-shading-threshold-at-25-percent|title=Comelec sides with Robredo, holds ballot shading threshold at 25 percent|last=News|first=Ina Reformina, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On July 31, Robredo voiced her support for the people of [[Basilan]] after a deadly terrorist attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/01/18/robredo-condoles-with-kin-of-basilan-blast-victims|title=Robredo condoles with kin of Basilan blast victims|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn August 5, Robredo voiced her support for the proposed anti-turncoat law in the House.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/06/18/robredo-wants-anti-turncoat-law-after-house-leadership-shakeup|title=Robredo wants anti-turncoat law after House leadership shakeup|last=News|first=Trishia Billones, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 13, President Duterte said that he would initiate a 'military junta' if ever Robredo becomes president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/14/18/duterte-prefers-military-junta-over-robredo|title=Duterte prefers military junta over Robredo|last=News|first=Dharel Placido, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 20, former President [[Noynoy Aquino]] expressed his confidence on Rodredo's leadership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/21/18/unlike-duterte-noynoy-confident-robredo-can-lead-ph|title=Unlike Duterte, Noynoy confident Robredo can lead PH|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 28, Robredo said that the [[martial law]] in [[Mindanao]] has failed to address threats in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/29/18/martial-law-failing-to-address-threats-in-mindanao-vp-robredo|title=Martial law failing to address threats in Mindanao: VP Robredo|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 29, she urged the House to increase funding for the Office of the Vice President after Duterte House allies voted to slash her office's budget by 100 million pesos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/29/18/robredo-urges-lawmakers-raise-ovp-budget-after-p100-m-slash|title=Robredo urges lawmakers: Raise OVP budget after P100-M slash|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 30, after President Duterte linked Robredo's [[Visual impairment|blind]] relative to the drug trade in Naga city, she rebuffed Duterte's claims and presented evidence of innocence. Duterte also called Naga city a 'hotbed of shabu' ([[methamphetamines]]). Duterte apologized afterwards for his mistake and wrong information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/08/31/18/robredo-camp-fires-back-at-duterte-on-naga-drugs-issue|title=Robredo camp fires back at Duterte on Naga drugs issue|last=News|first=Adrian Ayalin, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On August 31, Robredo rejected the idea of a [[dictatorship]] in a modern Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/01/18/quiet-courage-and-hard-work-robredo-rejects-dictatorship|title='Quiet courage and hard work': Robredo rejects dictatorship|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn September 1, senator [[Leila de Lima]] revealed that President Duterte planned to oust Vice President Robredo and replace her with [[Bongbong Marcos]], who lost the vice presidential election in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/02/18/de-lima-duterte-brews-plan-to-boot-robredo-tap-marcos|title=De Lima: Duterte brews plan to boot Robredo, tap Marcos|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On September 2, Robredo pushed for measures to aid government during the high inflation crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/09/03/18/robredo-pushes-for-measures-to-address-inflation|title=Robredo pushes for measures to address inflation|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On the same day, after [[rape]] remarks were made by Duterte, leading to a feminist backlash, Robredo stated that 'rape exists because of rapists' and supported the victims harassed by Duterte's speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/03/18/rape-exists-because-of-rapists-says-vp-robredo|title=Rape exists because of rapists, says VP Robredo|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On September 6, Robredo called Duterte's voiding of the [[amnesty]] of senator [[Antonio Trillanes]] a 'clear harassment' meant to silence critics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/06/18/robredo-duterte-order-voiding-trillanes-amnesty-clear-harassment|title=Robredo: Duterte order voiding Trillanes amnesty 'clear harassment'|last=News|first=Katrina Domingo, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On September 24, President Duterte apologized for falsely linking Robredo to an alleged ouster plot against him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/25/18/palace-clears-robredo-in-supposed-plot-to-oust-duterte|title=Palace clears Robredo in supposed plot to oust Duterte|last=News|first=Dharel Placido, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On September 28, Robredo visited the victims of a major landslide in [[Itogon, Benguet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/09/28/18/robredo-binisita-ang-mga-nasalanta-sa-itogon|title=Robredo binisita ang mga nasalanta sa Itogon|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn October 10, she blasted the House federal charter draft which sought to remove Robredo from the presidential line of succession.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/10/10/18/desperado-robredo-blasts-draft-charter-removing-her-from-succession|title='Desperado': Robredo blasts draft charter removing her from succession|last=News|first=Yasmin Pascual-Dormido, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On October 18, she lamented that 'democracy is facing challenges due to populist leaders.'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/10/19/18/democracy-facing-challenges-with-populist-leaders-robredo-says|title=Democracy facing challenges with populist leaders, Robredo says|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On October 24, 2018, Robredo officially launched the opposition senatorial slate for the 2019 senatorial elections,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/politics/elections/2019/215032-opposition-coalition-senatorial-slate-october-24-2018|title=LIVE: Opposition coalition introduces final Senate slate|last=Rappler.com|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> declaring that 'the opposition is alive.'<ref name=\"News\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/10/24/18/opposition-is-alive-vp-robredo-launches-senate-ticket|title=Opposition is 'alive': VP Robredo launches Senate ticket|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> The opposition candidates ran under the \"Otso Diretso\" slate, which included former senator [[Mar Roxas]], election lawyer Romulo Macalintal, Mindanao peace advocate [[Samira Gutoc-Tomawis]], human rights lawyer [[Chel Diokno|Jose Manuel Diokno]], former congressman [[Erin Ta\u00f1ada]], former solicitor general [[Florin Hilbay]], senator [[Bam Aquino]], and Magdalo party-list Rep. Gary Alejano.<ref name=\"News\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/01/27/oppositions-otso-diretso-gets-boost-from-robredo|title=Opposition\u2019s \u2018Otso Diretso\u2019 gets boost from Robredo|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, Robredo supported Australian missionary Sister Patricia Fox. The [[Bureau of Immigration (Philippines)|Bureau of Immigration]] had ordered Fox to be deported from the country as Fox was opposed to the deadly drug war.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/11/04/18/robredo-sister-fox-more-filipino-than-many-of-us|title=Robredo: Sister Fox 'more Filipino than many of us'|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On November 8, Robredo's team, which sought to aid the people of [[Boracay]], was barred from entering by government forces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/11/08/18/robredo-says-team-barred-from-boracay-during-closure|title=Robredo says team barred from Boracay during closure|last=News|first=Joyce Ann Clavecillas, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On November 17, Robredo lashed out at the 'special treatment' the government was providing for convicted criminal [[Imelda Marcos]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/11/17/18/robredo-sereno-binatikos-ang-special-treatment-kay-imelda-marcos|title=Robredo, Sereno binatikos ang 'special treatment' kay Imelda Marcos|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On November 21, Robredo called for transparency in government-sponsored deals with [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/11/21/18/vp-robredo-calls-for-transparency-in-ph-china-deals|title=VP Robredo calls for transparency in PH-China deals|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On November 26, Robredo called on the government to assure that troop deployments in [[Samar]], [[Negros Island|Negros]], and [[Bicol Region|Bicol]] would not lead to martial law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/11/26/18/robredo-govt-must-assure-troop-deployment-will-not-lead-to-martial-law|title=Robredo: Gov't must assure troop deployment will not lead to martial law|last=News|first=Adrian Ayalin, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, she hit out at the House for prioritizing the controversial federal charter that benefits political dynasties over economic bills that would benefit the poor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/12/05/18/robredo-hits-house-for-prioritizing-federal-charter-over-economic-bills|title=Robredo hits House for prioritizing federal charter over economic bills|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On December 10, Defense chief Lorenzana cleared Robredo of accusations of an alleged ouster plot against Duterte, stating that the accusations against Robredo were 'fake news again'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/12/11/18/fake-news-lorenzana-clears-robredo-in-alleged-duterte-ouster-plot|title='Fake news': Lorenzana clears Robredo in alleged Duterte ouster plot|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On December 21, Robredo condemned the assassination of Ako Bicol Partylist representative [[Rodel Batocabe]], a fellow Bicolano.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/12/22/18/batocabe-murder-must-not-be-the-new-normal-robredo-says|title=Batocabe murder \u2018must not be the new normal,\u2019 Robredo says|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On December 30, she led the [[Rizal Day]] rites after President Duterte did not attend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/multimedia/photo/12/31/18/robredo-leads-rizal-day-rites|title=Robredo leads Rizal Day rites|last=OVP/handout|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\n==== 2019 ====\nOn January 1, 2019, [[New Year's Day]], Robredo visited landslide-hit towns in [[Camarines Sur]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/02/19/robredo-visits-landslide-hit-camarines-sur-town|title=Robredo visits landslide-hit Camarines Sur town|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On January 15, 2019, she urged the Department of Foreign Affairs to take action amid the national data breach crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/happens/567|title=DFA data breach|website=philstar.com|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> On January 26, she condemned the deadly Sulu blast at a Catholic cathedral in Jolo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/27/19/arroyo-robredo-condemn-deadly-sulu-blast|title=Arroyo, Robredo condemn deadly Sulu blast|last=News|first=Maria Cecilia Butardo, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the May 2019 elections, news circulated on multiple social media platforms, mainly on Facebook, claiming that Vice President Robredo would resign as Vice President should the opposition slate ''Otso Diretso'' lose the election; Robredo later debunked the news as fake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2019/05/16/148954/leni-robredo-debunks-post-saying-she-will-resign-if-otso-diretso-loses/|title=Leni Robredo debunks post saying she will 'resign' if Otso Diretso loses|last=Malasig|first=Jeline|date=2019-05-16|website=Interaksyon|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2019, the [[Philippine National Police|PNP]]\u2013[[Criminal Investigation and Detection Group]] (CIDG) filed charges against Robredo and other members of the [[Otso Diretso|opposition]] for \"sedition, cyber libel, libel, ''estafa'', harboring a criminal, and [[obstruction of justice]]\".<ref name=\"bikoy0719\">{{cite news |title=Robredo, ilang taga-oposisyon kinasuhan ng PNP-CIDG ukol sa 'Bikoy' videos |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/07/19/19/robredo-ilang-taga-oposisyon-kinasuhan-ng-pnp-cidg-ukol-sa-bikoy-videos |work=ABS-CBN News |language=Tagalog}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sedition raps: Solons, bishop hit \u2018stupid\u2019 PNP |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1143908/sedition-raps-solons-bishop-hit-stupid-pnp |accessdate=July 20, 2019 |work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2019, the PET released the results of the initial recount, widening her lead over Sen. Marcos by 15,093 votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/242823-robredo-widens-lead-over-marcos-results-pet-recount-pilot-provinces|title=Robredo widens lead over Marcos in recount in 3 pilot provinces|last=Tomacruz|first=Sofia|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/712238/robredo-lead-over-marcos-widened-after-recount-in-3-provinces/story/|title=Robredo lead over Marcos widened after recount in 3 provinces|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/10/18/19/caguiao-carpio-robredo-lead-grew-by-15000-votes-in-initial-poll-protest-recount|title=PET: Robredo lead grew by 15,000 votes in initial poll protest recount|last=News|first=Mike Navallo, ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n\nOn October 23, 2019, Vice President Leni Robredo made a statement, saying that Duterte should allow the UN to investigate the war on drugs, and she added that a campaign has been \"a failure and a dent on the country's international image.\" Presidential spokesman [[Salvador Panelo]] slammed Robredo's remark, saying that her claim \"lacked factual basis.\" However, on October 27, 2019, Robredo clarified that she suggested for \"tweaks\" to the campaign and denied that she called to stop the war on drugs.\n\nOn November 4, 2019, Duterte assigned Robredo to be co-chairperson of the [[Inter-Agency Committee on Anti-Illegal Drugs]] (ICAD) until the end of his term in 2022, said presidential spokesman [[Salvador Panelo]]. <ref>[https://www.dpa-international.com/topic/duterte-appoints-vp-critic-war-drugs-lead-war-drugs-urn%3Anewsml%3Adpa.com%3A20090101%3A191105-99-586173]</ref>\n\n==== 2020 ====\nDuring the aftermath of the [[2020 Taal Volcano eruption]], she went to Batangas and Cavite, the most affected regions of the volcano eruption, on January 21st to distribute relief goods through her office and some partner organizations. The effort donated 1,500 food packs, 1,500 hygiene kits, and 1,500 sleeping mats for the victims. Leni herself also distributed [[Lugaw|lugaw]] (porridge) and [[Pandesal|pandesal]] to the victims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/249877-robredo-returns-batangas-cavite-give-more-aid-taal-volcano-eruption-evacuees|title=Robredo returns to Batangas, Cavite to give more aid to Taal evacuees|last=Cepeda|first=Mara|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn February 10, 2020, she was cleared of charges filed by the CIDG.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/725455/doj-clears-robredo-indicts-trillanes-and-10-others-for-conspiracy-to-commit-sedition/story/ | title=DOJ clears Robredo, indicts Trillanes and 10 others for 'conspiracy to commit sedition' | publisher=[[GMA News]] | date=February 10, 2020 | accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/251397-doj-resolution-conspiracy-commit-sedition-opposition | title=DOJ clears Robredo, charges Trillanes in sedition case | publisher=[[Rappler]] | date=February 10, 2020 | accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref> During the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|COVID-19 pandemic]], the Office of the Vice President provided free shuttle services for frontliners and emergency workers as the entire island of Luzon was put on an enhanced community quarantine. The office has also delivered 7,350 [[Personal protective equipment|personal protective equipment]] (PPEs) to nine hospitals, namely San Lazaro Hospital, the Philippine General Hospital, and UP-National Institutes of Health in Manila, and the Lung Center of the Philippines, Philippine Heart Center, Quirino Memorial Medical Center, Philippine Orthopedic Center, Veterans Memorial Medical Center, and East Avenue Medical Center in Quezon City. A total of \u20b117.3 million was raised for these donations, including food and care packages for the health workers and their families. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/robredo-donation-health-workers.html|title=Robredo donates gear to health workers, pledges free shuttle rides|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Issues ===\nNumerous [[fake news]] stories have been manufactured on [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]], [[YouTube]], and other blog sites against Robredo after she won the vice presidency in 2016. The instances of slander against her multiplied further after she expressed her dissent against the deadly [[Philippine Drug War]] of President [[Rodrigo Duterte]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/203309-leni-robredo-debunks-fake-news|title=Here's how Robredo debunks 'fake news' vs her|last=Cepeda|first=Mara|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> which has killed at least 20,000 Filipinos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/senator-rodrigo-duterte-drug-war-killed-20000-180221134139202.html|title=Senator: Rodrigo Duterte's drug war has killed 20,000|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> Robredo has demonstrated the falsehood of these statements against her. The majority of the fake news stories were fabricated by pro-Duterte bloggers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/breaking-news/2018/07/03/129890/rj-nieto-thinking-pinoy-free-speech-libel/|title=The libel charge against 'Thinking Pinoy' and the limits of free speech|last=Madarang|first=Catalina Ricci S.|date=2018-07-03|website=Interaksyon|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1019837/robredo-actions-of-mocha-uson-drew-olivar-do-not-help-duterte|title=Robredo: Actions of Mocha Uson, Drew Olivar do not help Duterte|last=Lalu|first=Gabriel Pabico|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> including those working under the Duterte government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//newsbreak/inside-track/201071-vice-president-leni-robredo-lies-bring-it-on|title=Robredo on lies: 'Bring it on'|last=Rappler.com|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nRobredo has been a constant victim of memes and \"fake news\" articles since taking office in 2016, some of which she claims emanate from a Senate source. Dealing with these, she said, was a \"test of character\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/05/12/vp-leni-intensify-efforts-to-punish-sources-of-fake-news|title=VP Leni: Intensify efforts to punish sources of fake news|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2017/12/24/vp-leni-in-2017-fake-news-snubs-impeachment-and-electoral-protest|title=VP Leni in 2017: Fake news, snubs, impeachment, and electoral protest|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2017/10/06/Robredo-hits-fake-news-sources.html|title=Robredo hits sources of fake news|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/994656/robredo-dealing-with-fake-news-public-criticism-a-test-of-character|title=Robredo: Dealing with fake news, public criticism a test of character|last=Ostria|first=Rey Anthony|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Leni Robredo's family July 2016.jpg|thumb|Robredo with her daughters.]]\nLeni was married to [[Jesse Robredo]], whom she met while working at the Bicol River Basin Development Program, from 1987 until his death from a [[2012 Philippine Piper Seneca crash|plane crash]] in 2012. The couple had three daughters: Jessica Marie \"Aika\" Robredo, Janine Patricia \"Tricia\" Robredo, and Jillian Therese Robredo.<ref name=\"Inquirer\"/><ref name=\"ABSCBNCOMwhirlwindromance\"/> Their eldest daughter, Aika,  was an executive assistant at the [[Office of Civil Defense (Philippines)|Office of Civil Defense]], while their second eldest, Tricia, is a medical student and was a [[UAAP]] basketball [[sideline reporter]] for [[National University (Philippines)|National University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=14 facts about the Philippines' 14th VP #10|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/image/nation/05/27/16/14-facts-about-the-philippines-14th-vp-10|accessdate=May 28, 2016|work=[[ABS-CBN News]]|date=May 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=de Vera|first1=Ruel|title=Aika Robredo\u2013Leni\u2019s secret campaign weapon|url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/227424/aika-robredo-lenis-secret-campaign-weapon|accessdate=May 28, 2016|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=April 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tricia Robredo's courtside reporting stint is for her dad|url=http://www.philstar.com/uaapseason76/articles/2013/08/16/1097911/tricia-robredos-courtside-reporting-stint-her-dad|accessdate=May 28, 2016|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=August 16, 2013}}</ref> Their youngest, Jilian, is currently studying biomolecular science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2018/08/23/1845174/robredos-daughter-study-new-york-university-full-scholarship|title=Robredo's daughter to study in New York University with full scholarship|website=philstar.com|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/994610/leni-robredo-graduation-harvard-ateneo-daughters-academic-rites|title=Proud mom VP Leni attends daughters\u2019 back-to-back academic rites|last=Esguerra|first=Anthony Q.|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nSince May 14, 2017, Robredo hosts her own public service radio program entitled ''BISErbisyong LENI'', aired on [[DZXL]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pasion|first1=Patty|title=Robredo to host own radio show starting May 14|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/169705-robredo-host-radio-show-may-14|accessdate=May 13, 2017|work=[[Rappler]]|date=May 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Honors and recognition ==\nRobredo was featured in an episode of ABS-CBN's drama anthology ''[[Maalaala Mo Kaya]]'' on February 6, 2016, three days before the official campaign period for national candidates in the 2016 elections. [[Dimples Romana]] played the role of Robredo, but [[Kaye Abad]] portrayed her in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections/2016/121192-leni-robredo-maalaala-mo-kaya-mmk|title=3 days before campaign, MMK to feature Robredo|work=[[Rappler]]|last=Cupin|first=Bea|date=February 3, 2016|accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2016, Robredo was awarded the Honorary Outstanding Woman Award of the Year 2016 by the [[Thailand|Thai]] government, coinciding with Thailand's Women's Day. The recognition was given to Robredo, citing her work and advocacy for [[women's empowerment]] and pushing for [[gender equality]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/141603-thailand-award-leni-robredo-women-empowerment|title=Robredo honored as 'outstanding woman' in Southeast Asia|last=Pasion|first=Patty|date=August 2, 2016|accessdate=August 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn August 23, 2016, Robredo was awarded the Most Influential Filipina Woman of the World award by Filipina Women's Network (FWN), a non-government organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2016/08/24/1616771/robredo-named-most-influential-filipina |title=Robredo named most influential Filipina |website=Philstar.com |date=August 24, 2016 |accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThree universities have conferred Robredo with honorary doctorates:\n\n* [[Polytechnic University of the Philippines]] (2015, Doctor in Public Administration),<ref name=\"Inquirer\" /> \n* [[University of Saint Anthony]] in [[Iriga]], [[Camarines Sur]], her home province (2017, Doctor of Humanities),<ref>{{cite news|last1=Patty|first1=Pasion|title=Look: Robredo receives honorary degree from Camarines Sur university|url=http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/inside-track/167390-robredo-honorary-degree-university-saint-anthony-camarines-sur|accessdate=April 21, 2017|work=[[Rappler]]|date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> \n* [[University of the Cordilleras]] (2017, Doctor of Laws).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Catajan|first1=Maria Elena|title=Robredo to youth: Be bearers of truth, empathy|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/161701|accessdate=February 20, 2019|publisher=[[SunStar]]|date=August 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title=Philippine vice presidential election, 2016<ref>https://ph.rappler.com/elections/2016/results/philippines/position/2/vice-president</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n|party=Liberal\n|candidate=Leni Robredo\n|votes=14,418,817\n|percentage=35.11%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=Independent politician\n|candidate=[[Bongbong Marcos]]\n|votes=14,155,344\n|percentage=34.47%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=Independent politician\n|candidate=[[Alan Peter Cayetano]]\t\n|votes=5,903,379\n|percentage=14.38%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=Independent politician\n|candidate=[[Francis Escudero]]\n|votes=4,931,962\n|percentage=12.01%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=Independent politician\n|candidate=[[Antonio Trillanes]]\n|votes=868,501\n|percentage=2.11%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=United Nationalist Alliance\n|candidate=[[Gregorio Honasan]]\n|votes=788,881\n|percentage=1.92%\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n|votes=41,066,884\n|percentage=100.00%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons}}\n* {{Official website|https://lenirobredo.com/}}\n* [http://www.congress.gov.ph/members/search.php?id=robredo-m Profile] at the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160703170051/http://www.bayangmatuwid.org/lp/candidate/Leni_Robredo/ Profile] at ''Bayang Matuwid''\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Offices and distinctions\n|list1=\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ph-lwr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Luis Villafuerte]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[House of Representatives of 